animal.description: Update: I'm no longer obsessed with escape. I now spend leisurely time in the office. HPC will tell you all about my training so that you can carry on where they leave off. After an intense play session I’m ready to spend quiet time with my folks. Training becomes a snap for the experienced handler. If you have an active lifestyle and would like to have a pal around for those midnight runs I’m your guy.***I have been micro chipped.

animal.description:
Also in need of a foster home ~ 
NMDOG LEWIS (aka Little LOUIE) is available for adoption! Please send an inquiry via this Petfinder link Or...to learn more about the NMDOG Adoption Program, please visit this link on our website - www.nmdog.org/adopt

Little LOUIE is appx 1 year old, but hes still very much a puppy. He currently weighs appx 55# & has received a full medical clearance. LEWIS walks well on his leash + harness, he loves to go for rides in the car & is very curious (yet somewhat guarded) about the world around him. One of his very fave things is exploring the Bosque with his person! .

We are seeking a Foster or FoReVeR home for LEWIS as an only Dog but he does enjoy having (supervised) playtime with his Doggie friends. LEWIS is looking for a loving & kind Hooman that will gently expose him to all of the good things life has to offer! He can be a little on the shy side at first but warms up quickly as soon as he knows he is safe with you. Someone with shy dog &/or Bully Breed experience is a plus! Cats are unknown but  we can cat test with an approved application! No human kids under 15 for LEWIS please. We want someone to lead LEWIS gently into the world because for a silly little Pittie like LOUIE...the world can be a big, scary place. Oh & when he barks, he sounds like he swallowed a squeaky toy :) But we think he will grow into his big boy bark someday! 
_____________________________________________

As an all volunteer, foster based, 501(c)3 non profit rescue, NMDOG is always in need of new, approved foster & adoptive homes in order to continue our Mission: to serve & protect New Mexico's Forgotten Dogs!! #UNchained 

If you see a dog you are interested in that says "in need of a foster home", we are currently seeking a temporary foster home for that dog in order to provide them with the cozy & loving experience of a home environment while we work hard to find their forever family. This also frees up space & funds, which enables us to save another life. There is never a cost to foster for NMDOG & you will have the dedicated support of the NMDOG TEAM every step of the way. We take the time to really get to know the needs & personalities of our kids & we go the extra mile to ensure we make the best possible match...setting our dogs & their humans up for success! To learn more about the NMDOG Foster Program, please visit this link on our website - www.nmdog.org/foster

Our adoption fee is $250 which includes; a 7 week NMDOG obedience/bonding class with your new Dog (classes are located in Abq & are also offered to our Foster Guardians at no charge), a complimentary vet wellness check & our dogs come with all of the supplies they need to get started on a trial adoption in their new home. All adopted dogs also receive free or discounted goodies & services from many of our awesome community partners!! Grooming, food, training, boarding, pet sitting & more.

NMDOG doesn't cut any corners when it comes to the care & placement of our dogs. When a dog enters the NMDOG program, they are guaranteed to receive the very best of care. All of our available dogs have received a full medical & behavioral clearance prior to placement. They are (at the very minimum) spayed or neutered, UTD on age appropriate vaccinations, microchipped, dewormed, Heartworm tested & currently on HW/flea & tick preventative. Due to the nature of our work, many of the dogs we rescue need much more extensive care before they are cleared for adoption. At NMDOG, we stand by our dogs for life & we make a promise to always be there for them (& their people) should they ever need us. .

Please contact us with your interest in becoming a treasured NMDOG Foster Guardian or FoReVeR Guardian Angel to one of our amazing dogs in need! Direct email contact for applications ~ TiffanyN@nmdog.org 
We look forward to hearing from you & answering any questions you may have. WooF!!

animal.description:
CLYDE is a great little dog for your family.  He is approx 6 years old, UTD shots, and will be neutered in Sept 2020 by one of our wonderful vet partners.  He will be better with a family that has children 10 years old or older.  We are working with him on housebreaking.  He gets along great with other small dogs.  He loves to run, play and jump.  He is learning what toys and treats are.  CLYDE has had a very, very rough 2020.  He needs a family that will give him some to time to trust and love them on his time frame.  He will be your buddy for life then. 

He came to Izzy's Place from an animal abuse case in Wyoming with 4 other male chihuahua's.  They had been left to die in a locked uhaul in wyoming in the middle of winter.  They then spent 5 months in a shelter as evidence for court.  Finally they came into rescue in July 2020 and are doing awesome.

So open your Heart and Home for CLYDE and you will never regret it.  Contact Izzy's Place to adopt this little guy.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Just finished her basic training. Ms Katie is ready for her debut. She just finished her basic training. She knows place, sit, go, here. She is crate trained. Smarest girl ever.
Katie runs with the pack (or more accurately, runs the pack) she is definitely an alpha personality. She is German Shepherd and Cattle Dog. Two working breeds that need a job and a lot of stimulous. She goes non stop and keeps everyone on their toes. She will be a great running companion once she is a bit older.
She is a talker and lets you know when there is an issue. If that is a puppy in the wrong crate, a puppy on the couch or, the group playing to rough - She has a lot to say.
Smart! She is potty trained. Does not soil her crate, figured out the doggie door weeks before I would have approved, but there is no stopping her when she sets her mind to learning something.
She sits for treats. Not because she was trained to, but because she watched the pack and learned. She is going to be an exceptional dog given the right owner.
She requires an active home. Because of her intelligence, she will become bored and then destructive which will not make anyone happy. Katie is a pleaser and learns very quickly.

Her perfect home will be older children, an active family and definitely a yard. Katie will do best with a companion dog in the family. She is not an apartment dog. She has 2 speeds, full out or asleep. If you think you can provide Katie with the stimulous and love that she will require, she will be an awesome dog.

=========================================================
Please contact app@aarfhouston.org for more information about this dog. You can apply online by clicking on Application .
Puppies that are under 4 months old cannot be adopted outside of our Veterinary Service area. Please call for specific locations. Children under 8 years old often are not a good match for our puppies and dogs. In order to protect both, your child and our rescued dogs/puppies from harm, we seldom if ever adopt to families with young children.
Once your application is approved, we will schedule a meet and greet at one of our adoption events. Thank you for considering a rescue! The adoption fee includes vaccinations, Bordetella, de-worming, rabies, spay/neuter and microchip. There is a an additional $12.99 fee for Home Again for a lifetime registration of the microchip.
Puppies cannot be adopted outside of the Houston area until they are spay/neutered after they are 4 months old. It is against the law in the State of Texas for a rescue not to be sterilized so we have to make sure it gets completed and that we have record of it.
NOTE: In our bios, we provide information based on our volunteer's experience with a particular dog; such as temperament, training, and ability to get along with others.
AARF is a 501(c)3 Non Profit, all breed, no kill organization. Our group is always in need of donations in order to continue to give the needed medical care to our rescues. Adoption fees do not begin to cover all of the medical costs. Any donation , no matter how small is a big help and is greatly appreciated. Please help us to continue to help them. Thank you.

animal.description:
Brandy is a 3-1/2-ish-year-old Hound mix weighing in at about 50 lbs. who was dumped on a back country road. Lucky for her, a Good Samaritan found her and she became a Big Fluffy. 

Brandy holds no grudges and is super sweet.  Brandy is good with lower key dogs as she prefers to be the queen of her home.  No cats for Brandy. She is a dream on a leash, so she would be a great walking buddy. She can be mouthy when she gets excited, so we think teens and up would be best.  Brandy is looking for someone that can give her lots of exercise and continue her training and give her a comfy and loveable home to live out her years to come.  Brandy will also need a tall fenced yard or someone dedicated to lots of leash walking.

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please apply online, at https://bigfluffydogs.com/adopt/adoption-application/ then email Debbie@BigFluffyDogs.com

Our main website, www.bigfluffydogs.com has more information about us and the rescue process. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters should understand that each home is different and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for 1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (i.e. a 4-month-old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break). 2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise. 3.) Socialization.  The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home. 4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded ten-fold, for years to come.  Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy.  Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time-consuming and can be expensive. All dogs require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well trained, well-socialized dog is more than worth the effort to get them there.

animal.description:
Bexley is a 6 year old girl, 25 lbs. Came to us after her family wanted to euthanize her after she went down because of IVDD She had surgery and has gotten physical therapy from her amazing foster mom and she is walking (a little wobbly, but effective and she has full bowel and bladder control)

Bexley is a sweet girl with all people. She would love a family where she was an only dog. She will tolerate some other dogs, but is the best she can be when it’s just her in a home. 

If you are interested in moving forward with the dog above, you are welcome to fill out an application on our website (www.dachshundrescuesouthflorida.com) which we will process to find out a bit more about what kind of doxie would be a good match for your home.  We ask potential forever homes to fill out an application as the first step in moving forward with any of our dogs for three reasons:

 -  We process all applications before making any introductions so we can help ensure people will be good home and have the right environment for a doxie

-  Asking potential families to fill out an application helps us ensure we are utilizing our efforts working with those who are serious about adopting

 - Lastly, this process minimizes visitors and interruptions to our foster homes for without whom, we would not be able to operate!
 
Please join us on Facebook as well to see the day to day operations of our rescue; www.facebook.com/dachshundrescuesouthflorida

animal.description: Have wheels will travel! Emma doesn't let the little things slow her down. This sweet baby girl has been through some trauma in her short life, and is ready to see how good life can be! Emma is happy and active, but needs help with her day-to-day activities due to some back leg paralysis. It is uncertain whether her paralysis is permanent at this point, but she is content to use her wheels to motor around for now. All she asks of her humans is to help her with going potty, follow up with her physical therapy, and give her plenty of love! Miss Emma loves to cuddle, play with her toys, and chew on bones. Since she has been busy learning to use her wheels, she hasn't had as much time to socialize with other dogs. She will need slow introductions with other dogs and playtime with gentle dogs due to her current condition. She seems very curious about cats, so they may not make the best roommates or will need very slow introductions. This silly girl is looking for an adult family that knows what it is like to rely on others for help. She needs the time and patience to trust those that will allow her to be her happiest! Are you ready to give Miss Emma the TLC she needs? Her foster family is ready to share what a day in the life of Emma is like. Come meet this sweet soul!

animal.description:
BELLA (female)
Breed: Dobie/Pyrenees (per DNA results)
Age: Approx. 1 year
Weight: Approx. 65- 70 lbs.
Adopter Experience: Advanced
Adoption Status: Available
Bella is sweet, affectionate and playful girl but she's also high energy. Having previously lived in a home, she does have some basic training under her paws. Bella has done well with the dogs we have introduced her to but needs firm, strong handler experience and a home with no other dogs for now. Bella would be a great companion for an experienced, active home, due to her size and energy a home with space for her to romp and play is most ideal.
Due to her size and energy, a home with children under fifteeen would not be an ideal match for Bella.

ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS & PROCEDURES

Mutt Match L.A. does not adopt out of state nor do we adopt on a first come first serve basis but rather to the home that is best suited for each particular dog and breed. An application, home check, contract and adoption fee are required for all adoptions. All dogs will be, or required to be, spayed/neutered, current on vaccinations and microchipped before adoption. Most of our dogs are from local LA area shelters, we generally have no prior history for them.

Adoption fees vary between $400 - $500 for puppies 8 weeks - 5 years, $350 6 - 9 years and $300 for dogs over 9 years. Adoption fee covers spay/neuter, vaccinations, microchip, a wellness check, any additional medical expenses necessary and of course all the love and daily care we take with each dog before they are adopted.

We believe a well behaved dog is a happy dog and companion. Therefore, we require at least one session with one of our recommended behaviorists for a reduced fee which is not included in the adoption fee.

For additional information or questions, please email us at info@muttmatchla.org. To submit an application, please visit us at www.muttmatchla.org. Mutt Match L.A. is an all volunteer rescue, please allow at least 48 hours for a returned response of all inquires.

Thank you! We look forward to hearing from you soon.

Bo is outgoing, friendly and loves to make new friends. He's mellow and enjoys lounging in a sunny spot, hanging out with his human friends and going on short walks. He won't bother you much unless you let him know you are ready for a round of tug-of-war, then he happily accepts the challenge. He also enjoys modeling on the side, becoming the inspiration for Corridor Rescue's logo. 

He has made friends with a couple of female dogs at our kennel, but his all-time favorite girl is Odessa. They were seen together for years on the street, and reunited about a year after Bo was rescued. Bo and Odessa share a kennel the majority of the time at Corridor and would be happiest being adopted together.

Bo is a well behaved guy and keeps his room neat and clean. He knows sit, stay and will come when you call his name off leash. He loves to do tricks for treats, of course. His favorite commands are sit and shake. 

Bo does have some arthritis, but still enjoys life to the fullest. We would love for him and Odessa to have a forever home in their golden years. Relaxing on couches, playing tug-of-war in the yard and knowing the safety and love that comes with a forever home.

***

Transport is available and can be discussed on an individual basis.

animal.description:
**This dog is with Corridor Rescue in Houston, Texas**

Like a lot of our rescue pups, we're not exactly sure what breed Harry is, but we do know this goofy playful boy is a ton of fun! He's quickly become a staff favorite with his happy personality. Harry loves all the people and has done great in all his doggie playgroups.

Harry requires a strict vegetarian diet and allergy shots. He struggled with allergies for a long time, but he's finally found something that works, and it shows! Harry is a happy guy and his coat is all grown in; which was something that was lagging behind in his recovery due to the allergies.

Harry is now in a foster home and, as expected, he's doing awesome. He lives with 4 dogs and 4 cats. He also comes into contact with donkeys and horses and chickens and does well with all of them, also.

Harry is an amazing dog, but there are a few considerations with adopting him. He will need to be under the care of a veterinary dermatologist likely for life. If he has anything that's not on his strict diet, he will have an allergic reaction, causing a trip to the dermatologist. This is also a reason we do not believe Harry will do well in a home with children. As almost everyone knows, kids unintentionally (and sometimes intentionally) drop things on the floor, leave toys laying around, etc. And not only is Harry susceptible to allergic reactions, he is also susceptible to eating things he shouldn't. He's already had surgery to remove a rope toy he found somewhere from his stomach. He cannot have any toys, but can have Nylabone-type toys WITH SUPERVISION as he likes to chew. Harry's allergies require prescription food, prescription allergy injections and prescribed medicated baths. This will very likely be for life.

He is 100% worth all of this. He's a wonderful dog who loves his people and he's very easy to love. 

***

**This dog is with Corridor Rescue in Houston, Texas**

I'm still looking for a home... I'm an athletic, anxious boy and would do best with someone who is home most of the time. I do not like to be alone. I am what they call a "sensitive soul."
If there is another dog in the home, there MUST be a meet 'n' greet. Davis will only do well with a very laid back, passive dog as he feeds off another dog's emotions. He would do best as the only dog in the home. 
He is a very loving boy and really just wants to make his people happy and to be with them as much as possible.

I like dogs, I like cats (the lazy ones only), I like hanging out, I like walks. I do have energy to spare, so a home with people who really like to spend time with me would be great. I have some learning to do, but I am willing to listen and I can't wait to show my people what a good boy I can be.

I'm a pretty easy guy to get along with! If you'd like to see that for yourself, fill out an application to meet me! I'd love to meet you!

Davis has separation anxiety and would do best in a home where someone is with him the majority of the day or is able to have someone come over and let him out or bring him to doggie daycare. He loves his people and will sit in laps, on feet, etc., to keep you near. He also very much prefers to sleep in bed with his people.
He's a very sweet, sensitive, athletic boy who will require time, energy and patience, but the love that comes back will be more than worth it. He has flourished in his foster home with his human parents and furry siblings. We can't wait to see what he does in his forever home.

animal.description:
**This dog is with Corridor Rescue in Houston, Texas** 

Hi! It's me, Odessa! I'm still at the kennel, looking for a home with my forever home with my best boy, Bo! 

I was rescued in March 2018, after living on the streets for years. Once at the kennel, it took me a minute to warm up to the staff, but it wasn't too long before I figured out that the rescued life is a much better life to be living. Soon, they introduced me to Bo, who I had hung out on the streets with for a long time. It was so fun to see him! He's pretty much the only dog I like.

Bo and I like to go for walks, play tug-of-war, and nap. Bo & I both have arthritis, so our walks are short and our play sessions aren't as long as they used to be either. But that's OK! There's one other thing I really like--CAR RIDES! Yep! A good ol' Sunday drive really makes me happy. 

One thing I am not a fan of is thunderstorms. I need some comfort to get through the storms...they really freak me out. 

Please consider adopting some oldies, but goodies! Bo and I really want a good home together to live out the rest of our days.

animal.description:
***Due to Covid, the "dog dry" situation in many pounds and a backlog of already approved adopters, we are only accepting applications for dogs with a name and bio on Petfinder.

Visit our website for more information on dog availability:  https://www.lelrr.org/

Please follow us on Facebook and Instagram LELRR501c3

We very much appreciate your interest in adopting a Labrador in need through LELRR. Please understand that this is a process, and it may take some time to both review and process your application, as well as to potentially adopt one of our Labs. One of the reasons that we ask for an application fee ($25) is that it takes the limited resources and time of our Trustees and volunteers to thoroughly review and process your application. (This fee is deducted from the adoption fee when you adopt.)

Please be patient; and be respectful of the volunteers and fosters that will work with you through this process. No one is paid, it is a labor of love, and we do our best to respond to applications and inquiries in a timely manner. 

That said, there is a reason that we ask applicants to specify the name of a dog in our application. With limited resources, we want to make sure that we are processing applications that will result in a successful adoption of one of our Labs in need. We cannot guarantee that you will be able to adopt the specific Lab that you are inquiring about. We always have more qualified applicants than we have Labradors available for adoption. 

Our job, and most especially the job of our fosters, is to place their dogs with the adopters that are the best fit for that specific Lab, and will offer them the best chance for success. If the Lab you originally applied for is adopted to someone else, please don't take it personally; and remember that we are always bringing in new Labs in need. One of them may very well be the perfect fit for your home. 

Your patience and understanding of our process is very much appreciated. Thank you!

animal.description:
Meet Toby! He is one fun-loving dude with an incredible zest for life. Toby loves to play and have adventures, but he is equally as happy to snuggle up and chill. He is incredibly food motivated and won’t hesitate to remind you it’s mealtime. Toby has a goofball personality and loves to make you laugh. He is also an exceptionally talented soccer player and would like to continue to work on this skill in his new home. 

In Toby’s short life he has already had several homes and been handed some bad luck. He does have a bite history due to a fear based reaction to a scary situation he was in. He is nervous in some situations and needs guidance to build his confidence and help him learn how to act in situations he’s unsure of. He is a dog that learns incredibly quickly and craves boundaries and structure. If he is provided the stability he needs, he will continue to flourish into the well balanced and good boy that he is.  

Toby’s ideal home is a calmer setting where he can be his adopter’s “only child”. Although he is dog social, he would do best in a dog free home to ensure he is setup for success. He needs a firm and experience handler who can give him boundaries and routine. Playing with other dogs is very exciting and he would love to have play dates with other large, well-mannered dogs outside of the home. A home with cats or children won’t be suitable for Toby. 

To apply to adopt Toby, please visit our website at: https://newcollar.co/adopt-a-dog

animal.description:
Amora is a pit bull terrier/boxer/american bulldog mix, is 4-5 years old and weighs approximately 60 pounds. Gunner is a purebred cane corso and turned 5 years old on October 24th, 2020. He is a BIG DOG and weighs 120 pounds. He is a gentle giant and not a jumper. Both are active and playful, but do have their calm moments. They like to play tug-of-war with each other and their humans. Neither growl or nip if you take away toys or food. Amora LOVES to swim and would do well in a home with a pool. Gunner prefers to stay out of the water. Amora also likes to play fetch. They are very smart pups and have learned a few commands. Amora knows: come, stay, go outside, leave it, sit. Gunner knows: go outside, leave it, sit. Amora is fully house-broken and working on leash-training. Gunner is working on house-training with the assistance of Amora, but will need time, effort and patience from his adopters to complete it. He also requires a bit of patience to learn what he can and cannot chew: lots of toys will help! He is not leash-trained due to his size and strength. There are so many amazing things about Gunner: he adapts to your energy very easy, he is caring, his is alert, does not bite, loves feet, he is truly the best kind of friend. Both are good with kids and very sweet and loving with their family. Amora is as loyal as can be. She is a well behaved dog and she is great with kids and guests. She is protective and alert, very active, house broken. She always aims to please her humans. She is dog selective and does not get along with small animals or other large breed females. She does perfectly with Gunner and he's all she wants in a canine companion! Gunner is good with other dogs and, despite his size and strength, he is quite submissive to other canines. He is not a very confident dog and is a bit timid. His sister's confident, outgoing personality perfectly balances out his own. Amora and Gunner would make a wonderful pair to a home looking for a couple of goofy, gentle, loving large breed buds. They really adore each other and howl/cry whenever they are apart. Their adoption fee as a pair is $685 and covers the costs of spay/neuter, all core vaccines (Rabies and Distemper/Parvo), microchips and microchip registrations. If you are interested in adopting, please complete an application, available on our website, poochmatch.com, under the adoption tab and please read the paragraphs below for more details on our process.

If this listing is still posted, we are still accepting applications for him/her. We do not do out-of-state adoptions on highly adoptable dogs; we would only consider out-of-state adoptions for dogs that prove hard-to-place locally. We cannot hold dogs, please submit your application when you are ready to adopt.

UPDATE: ADOPTION EVENTS CANCELLED DUE TO PANDEMIC AND SOCIAL DISTANCING. If you are interested in meeting any Poochmatch dog at our weekly adoption event on Saturdays at the Petsmart in Yorba Linda, CA (5521 Mirage St.) between 1-5 PM, please fill out an application from our website, poochmatch.com, and submit it no later than 11 AM on Fridays. Upon receipt AND approval, the dog you are interested in meeting will be made available to meet on a Saturday. Due to the high volume of dogs and puppies in our foster homes, it is impossible to bring them all every Saturday. The only way to ensure that the dog that you are interested in will be at the adoption event is to FILL OUT AN APPLICATION AND BE APPROVED. Otherwise, we cannot guarantee that the dog you are interested in will be at our adoption event. If you cannot make the time frame of our events, appointments can be made at another time and location solely at the discretion of the foster parent. Please understand that private appointments will be coordinated to meet the convenience of the foster parent/transporter. We cannot hold dogs, please submit your application when you are ready to adopt.

All adoption fees cover the mandatory and non-negotiable spay/neuter, rabies, microchip, microchip registration, full sets of core vaccinations (rabies and 1 set of distemper/parvo for adults, 4 for puppies) and deworming. In an effort to create a safe environment for our potential adopters and our staff, we have changed our protocols and procedures during these difficult times. Due to the fact that there is such a high demand, we are sticking with strict protocol to not adopt out of Southern California. We apologize for this inconvenience and difficulty to be able to get in touch with us while there is an overwhelming desire and demand to adopt at this time. We appreciate your understanding and patience as we navigate through these difficult times with every intention to keep the public and our staff safe.

animal.description:
Amora is a pit bull terrier/boxer/american bulldog mix, is 4-5 years old and weighs approximately 60 pounds. Gunner is a purebred cane corso and turned 5 years old on October 24th, 2020. He is a BIG DOG and weighs 120 pounds. He is a gentle giant and not a jumper. Both are active and playful, but do have their calm moments. They like to play tug-of-war with each other and their humans. Neither growl or nip if you take away toys or food. Amora LOVES to swim and would do well in a home with a pool. Gunner prefers to stay out of the water. Amora also likes to play fetch. They are very smart pups and have learned a few commands. Amora knows: come, stay, go outside, leave it, sit. Gunner knows: go outside, leave it, sit. Amora is fully house-broken and working on leash-training. Gunner is working on house-training with the assistance of Amora, but will need time, effort and patience from his adopters to complete it. He also requires a bit of patience to learn what he can and cannot chew: lots of toys will help! He is not leash-trained due to his size and strength. There are so many amazing things about Gunner: he adapts to your energy very easy, he is caring, his is alert, does not bite, loves feet, he is truly the best kind of friend. Both are good with kids and very sweet and loving with their family. Amora is as loyal as can be. She is a well behaved dog and she is great with kids and guests. She is protective and alert, very active, house broken. She always aims to please her humans. She is dog selective and does not get along with small animals or other large breed females. She does perfectly with Gunner and he's all she wants in a canine companion! Gunner is good with other dogs and, despite his size and strength, he is quite submissive to other canines. He is not a very confident dog and is a bit timid. His sister's confident, outgoing personality perfectly balances out his own. Hello there!
My name is Molly.  My foster mom calls me a social butterfly because I love people! Humans are the best, aren't they?  I'm a little nervous around new dogs, but once I get to know them, I want to be best friends!  
I was rescued with my 2 babies from the hot and dangerous streets, so I am almost healed up from severe mange - so glad those days are over!

animal.description: Meet Pup Pup! He needs a special person, but he knows you're out there. We know it too! Pup Pup is pretty fearful with new people, especially men. He is also handshy. Pup Pup needs you to go slowly it is worth it once you've won him over! That's exactly what shelter staff and volunteers did with Pup Pup: took it slowly. Didn't rush things. Made sure he was comfortable with them. Watched his body language. Gave him LOTS of treats! And now Pup Pup has some shelter BFFs, including men, who look forward to spending time with him. Once you're in Pup Pup's inner circle, he acts like, well, a dog! He plays fetch, runs around with his toys, checks in with you for affection (and treats!). And you know that y'all's relationship is the real deal when he rolls over to ask for a belly rub. Pup Pup needs an adopter willing to take the time to get to know him. That means multiple visits at the shelter to start creating that bond. Someone who recognizes that he will always need slow, repeated introductions with new people. Someone who understands that he has been through a lot in his short life and who wants to help him heal and thrive. Pup Pup needs a pet-free home that is adult-only and low-traffic. Pup Pup appears to be house trained but may need a little refresher course in a new home. Pup Pup may always remain cautious and fearful with strangers. He will go home with tons of support from the Orange Dot Crew (a volunteer advocacy group at the shelter), a goody bag of enrichment items, and free training support thanks to Friends of AAC and their Behavior Assistance Program! Click here to view my paperwork.

Ripley is one special, tough and amazing girl! She appears to have a lot of German Shepard in her and is super smart, energetic and absolutely loves the people she trusts. She can be fearful, intimidated and nervous around people she is unfamiliar with and needs an experienced owner to help her become more well socialized. Due to her lacking some basic social skills, we feel she should not go to a home with any children. A patient owner who can also help her by working with a trainer and managing her fear of new people would be a great match for Ripley. With her trusted people she is often cuddly, affectionate and loves to curl up on your lap as if she were the size of a Chihuahua. She also can't get enough hugs and belly rubs!
Ripley has a difficult time making dog friends because she just doesn't realize her own size and strength; but not in an aggressive way. So if she goes to a home with another dog, she will need two onsite visits at TVR before being adopted to make sure everyone gets along. Ripley seems to prefer male dogs and can be a handful and too rowdy for some dogs to play with so she shouldn't go to a home with a puppy or small dogs. She's a bit of a Tomboy! 

If you're an experienced dog owner looking for an active, smart and affectionate best friend, Ripley might just be the companion you've been waiting for!

animal.description:
BACKSTORY:
We got word that a chocolate nugget of puppy goodness ended up at an area animal control due to no fault of his own. That’s no place for any dog to be, let alone a youngin. He’s young, goofy, had absolutely no manners, and needs to grow into his legs. Basically, he’s a perfect crazy puppy!

EDUCATION:
* Sit
* Down
* Stay
* Leave it
* Come
* Paw
* Touch
* Crate trained
* House trained
* He knows 'show me' and he'll play bow at the things he wants like bowing at shoes for walks, the door for potty breaks, and the water bowl for a refill
ACTIVITIES THIS CUTIE ENJOYS:
* Treats: not picky and he loves carrots
* Food: he'd like eggs and spinach, please
* Toys: Westpaw brand toys, bones, Chuck-It balls
* Walks: superstar on leash and he likes his walks, don't forget ?
* Sleeping
* Playing
* Chewing on stuff
* Playing tug
* Fetch
* Head and ear rubs

SKILLS:
* Dogs: friendly
* Kids: overexcited, he doesn't realize how big he is, we recommend ages 10+
* People: friendly, overexcited
* Cats: unknown

CHALLENGES:
* Not a fan of the regular vacuum but the Roomba is ok
* Normal puppy behaviors like chewing, jumping, and mouthiness
* Not a fan of getting his nails clipped or his ears cleaned, he just needs 2 people and treats to get the job done

Chip is a very active, playful, cuddly 3 year old Min Pin/Chihuahua ("Chi-Pin") mix boy who will never leave you lonely or bored. Chip will follow you everywhere and jump up and down like a pogo stick when he wants you to pick him up.  He loves to be loved on! This sweet girl loves affection, lounging on the bed and getting lots of cuddles and belly rubs. She does well with big dogs but not littles.

animal.description:
**ADOPTION APPLICATION REQUIRED via our website Rarerescue.org**

ADOPTION FEES: Our Adoption Fees vary based on adoptability to help all of the animals in our organization. Please make sure to read the adoption fee below in the bio.

BREEDS: We are not breed experts. The breed(s) listed for each adoptable are best guesses or suggestions.

STEPS TO ADOPT:

Read the adoptable’s bio below, including their adoption fee

Read  ADOPTION PROCESS page under the "Adopt" section

Complete the  DOG ADOPTION APPLICATION (located on our website RARErescue.org)

*Applications will be attended to before general inquiries. 

We understand that it is important to you to find the right fit for your family. We feel the same way! The application is important and necessary for this reason. 

All of our Adoptables are:

*spayed/neutered

*up to date on vaccines

*heartworm tested if six months or older (and kept on heartworm preventative and treated for heartworms if positive when entering our program)

*microchipped prior to adoption

BASIC INFO about Julius:

Suggested Breed(s): Staffordshire Terrier/Rottweiler

Gender:  Male/Neutered

Approx. Age or D.O.B:  1/5/2018 (Approx 2 years)

Approx. Weight:  67 lbs

Coat Type:  Short

Good around most dogs:  Yes

Good around most cats:  Unknown

Energy Level:  Medium 

Fence yard may be required:  Yes

Any other specifics: 

Julius loves people, so he would enjoy being the only dog, he would also do well with a submissive, playful female dog
Crate trained, house trained 
Great in the car, loves to ride
Where did Julius come from?: We rescued Julius from a small rural municipal shelter that euthanizes for space; he was so excited to take his freedom ride!

Adoption Fee: $85.00

Will you be a Hero in Julius's story?

Visit our website/Click on Adopt to APPLY today!  RARErescue.org

Please REMEMBER, All of our Adoptables are:

*spayed/neutered
*up to date on vaccines
*heartworm tested if six months or older (and kept on heartworm preventative and treated for heartworms if positive when entering our program)
*microchipped prior to adoption



PLEASE NOTE: We are a non-profit organization without municipal or government funding. Veterinary/Medical expenses are constant for an animal rescue. Our adoption fees not only help to provide vetting and care for the animal being adopted, but they also help to cover heartworm treatments and other treatable ailments that many animals, that would otherwise be euthanized, need in order to be made available for adoption.

Please understand that adopting an animal is a LIFETIME COMMITMENT to that animal and there will be veterinary expenses throughout their life that can often cost several hundreds, if not thousands of dollars (without pet insurance), especially without annual checkups and preventative care.  As a potential family for this pet you are responsible for their safety and that includes keeping them on your property.

***If you are not in the middle Tennessee area, transport can potentially be arranged to approved homes, depending on distance and local adaptability. We normally do not allow adoptions outside of 1.5 hours driving distance.

Thank you for choosing to adopt, foster, or aid in the rescue efforts of RARE!

animal.description:
Henry is a fun and excitable 3 year old boy who is ready to begin his new adventure! Henry is an active and energetic pupper who would be perfect for an active family. Henry isn't afraid to get out in the great outdoors and explore with his nose to the ground! A child free household would be Henry's perfect living situation as he does struggle with food and bowl guarding- this spoiled baby was never taught to share! animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.All of the animals posted on our site have been temperament tested. While not all are in the immediate area, once we have processed and approved your application, we will move the dog to our adoptive area for you to meet, greet and hopefully adopt. Sometimes we will have more than one application on a dog. That does not mean it automatically goes to another family but you should be aware of the fact that until you are approved and set up for the meet/greet.. the dog could get adopted by another applicant.
NOTE- TREVOR IS LISTED AS A COURTESY FOR ANOTHER RESCUE ORGANIZATION. PLEASE SEE CONTACT INFO BELOW. Trevor has been with the rescue now for almost 3 years. Why? We are not sure. He has been overlooked so many times and it really surprises us! Trevor came into the rescue, basically on death's door. He had pneumonia and the most severe case of heartworm we have ever experienced. Trevor has since been treated, saw a Cardiologist and is a happy, healthy boy! He does have some damage to his heart but that doesn't mean he won't live a long life. It just means he can't run a marathon with you!

Trevor is around 6-7 years old and is the most polite boy. He walks wonderfully on a leash and loves to co-pilot in the car. Trevor's favorite pastimes are napping and cuddling. He LOVES treats and even tap dances in excitement waiting for a treat. He really is a sweet, amazing dog!

Trevor will need to be the only dog in the home and we would prefer he be in a home with older children.

Note from his foster: Trevor has been with me for over two years now. He has changed a lot from the dog that came to my house two years ago, but his fun loving personality has remained. He may not be the next star student in an obedience class, but he makes up for that with the unconditional love he gives and happy go lucky attitude. His life before he was rescued couldn't have been that great, considering the condition he was in at the time. But he has long forgotten the bad things that happened to him, and looks at each day as a new opportunity for fun, food and love. He always "tap dances" when food or treats are involved. animal.description:
Hi everyone! I’m Slater, but my OCPBR family calls me Nugget. I was being given away when I was barely two weeks old, and just a wee nugget. (see what I did there?) Lucky for me, OCPBR scooped me up, and I was taken to my first foster home where I was bottle fed and nursed back to health. Once I got big and strong, I came to my current foster home where I have two extra large 4 legged foster siblings. Seeing as I didn’t get to grow up with my litter mates, being able to learn and grow from my foster family has been super helpful and important. I’m super energetic and need someone who’s going to play with me, so a home with a senior dog would not be the best fit for me. I am a silly, fun puppy, but I do not like being hugged or restrained so a home with children under the age of 12 isn’t a good fit for me. I completed puppy obedience training classes and I attend structured daycare 3 days a week where I am playing with new friends of all breeds and sizes and ages, I really like small dogs. I am crate trained and house trained, but sometimes have potty accidents in new environments like puppies do. I do have to eat a low protein diet, otherwise my body produces bladder stones. Don’t worry OCPBR has already paid for all of the tests, so you will just need to feed me appropriate food and treats please. 

At OCPBR, we do a foster to adopt with all of our puppies going to their new families. If you have another dog(s), the dog(s) must be completely friendly with puppies, other dogs and people. Please no senior dogs, puppies are young and energetic and need a playmate for their development. Plus it’s unfair to senior dogs to have to endure normal puppy energy. They must also be current on vaccines. The foster must be willing and able to participate in our foster care program to include, ongoing obedience training and socialization.

If you’re interested in Slater, please go to https://www.ocpbr.org/images/2019/08/OCPBR-Foster-to-Adopt-Application-2019.pdf and send in the app to adopt@ocpbr.org.

animal.description:
Looks like: Rat Terrier Mix
Female, 11 years old, 18 pounds

Dear little Rainier was saved by a good Samaritan who saw her in danger along a busy highway, and we are so glad! Ranier's foster mom lovingly calls this mellow pup a "space cadet", which is one of her most endearing qualities. This sweet gal is initially a bit shy of new people, but quickly becomes sociable with humans and is nonreactive to other pups. Rainier is a perfect angel with kitties too, according to her foster mom, who reports that her cats sit on Ranier and groom her! She is an easy-going, trusting little soul who will follow you around the house. She just wants to be where YOU are, in case you are handing out pets or head scratches. She is so grateful for your attention! She gets a bit agitated when left alone, so she likely will be happiest in a home where somebody is at home most of the time. Treats and toys make transitions easier for her. Ranier has been fine socializing with children. 

Rainier seems to have a hearing deficit but is learning to respond to signal training - isn't it wonderful that old dogs CAN learn new tricks? She walks well on leash, stopping here and there to read her "pee-mail." Her energy level is fairly low, so short walks suit her just fine. 

Ranier's goal in life is just to be at your side - she's ready for your home and YOUR LOVE. Her ideal home would be a quiet one, maybe even with another mellow doggy friend who could show her the ropes. Rainier is so deserving of all the care and attention you can give her! 

She came to Peace of Mind from the Hollister Animal Shelter.

animal.description:
Smokie is a 65lb lean lab melon headed mix boy who is ready to take on the world by your side. He has the most beautiful coloring. In the light, you can see a gorgeous red brindle coat. Other times, he looks ebony and grey. Whatever he is, this boy is stunning and carries a regal presence. Just 3 years old, Smokie ensured more than his fair share of hardship and sorrow. He came to us as a cruelty case where a family member stabbed him in an effort to anger his owner. Smokie required extensive surgery to repair the stab wound and the hernia it caused. Abuse does not start there. However, Smokie feels nothing but love in his heart. 

Due to his traumatic past, Smokie entered a board and train program. By the time he completes his program, Smokie will complete his canine good citizenship test and be ready for a forever or foster home! Smokie is wonderful with other dogs, big and small. He loves to play tug of war, bounce around, and cuddle with them. In fact, Smokie loves any excuse to cuddle. Just tell him, ‘The sun is setting real low, big guy’ or sing ‘Goodnight Sweetheart Goodnight’ to him and Smokie will curl into you and start the snore train! 

Smokie is housebroken, crate trained, and is very comfortable in his crate. Also, this boy walks beautifully on a leash and heels like a pro! He knows all his commands and will love to show off his skills for you. 

Smokie loves his human and will do anything for them. For this reason, he needs someone that can help him understand that they do not need his protection- just love. The ideal home for this boy would be adult only and with someone who can provide him with boundaries. Smokie would be fine in an apartment, urban, suburban, or rural environment. He would love to be the only child or have a doggy sibling. We don't know how he is with cats. He just asks that you and him spend time together and keep his training up! This boy thrives on having a job or purpose!

His training comes with private lessons, if you are close enough. If not, we can arrange for ongoing lessons another way. 

If interested in adopting or fostering Smokie, please email us at twentypawsrescue@gmail.com or info@twentypawsrescue.com. Please note we respond to all emails. If you do not hear back from us, please follow up! Sometimes, emails get lost in cyberspace.

animal.description: Asher is in pretty rough shape but we are working with the vet clinic to get him all fixed up. He joined us this week from the Hazard, KY shelter. He is an older boy and has A LOT of medical going on, including a 3/5 heart murmur, needed dental, several lumps and bumps and some swelling and loss of range of motion in his right front leg. He is a little bit timid but very sweet and has a great personality and is very friendly :) Asher did very well with his dog test at the shelter. 9/5: Asher is heartworm negative and his chest x-rays look good despite the heart murmur. We are waiting on his bloodwork results and if they are good, we will get him scheduled for tumor removal and dental surgery. He did start on Enalapril for his heart and has been on antibiotics for the swollen spots on his legs. X-rays and testing did not show any signs of bone cancer, thank goodness. His leg is looking better and he is getting around better on it. He is incredibly sweet and is doing great with everyone. An owner did come forward for him but after a family discussion, they decided it was best for him to stay with the rescue so he can get all of the medical care that he needs. We know that was a difficult decision for them and we are thankful that they put his needs first and that they have entrusted us with his care. We also found out that his real name is Buster so that is what we are actually calling him :)9/10: Asher will be having an ultrasound tomorrow to check his heart for surgery and if all is good he will get his tumor and bumps removed and get some much needed dental work done early next week. Asher will be in need of a foster home and will likely be ready to travel as soon as the weekend of 9/26.10/2 UPDATE: Asher was cleared for surgery and came through it beautifully! He did great and the best news....his two tumors were benign!! His leg is all healed up and he is getting around perfectly. He still has a spot of skin healing on his chest but with medication and therapy it is looking much better.11/1: Asher who we are now calling by his real name Buster arrived at his Minnesota foster home last night after a super long day of transport from Kentucky. The spot on his chest cleared up enough that they were able to close it up. He is taking his meds like a champ and will get his suture stitches out soon. We are sure his foster fursister Susie will show him the ropes!!
animal.name: Asher aka Buster

animal.description:
Senior Hearts Rescue and Renewal is the only licensed senior dog rescue organization in Western Pennsylvania. We do not have a shelter or a public facility. ALL of our dogs reside in foster homes in the greater Pittsburgh, PA area. 

We are a 100% volunteer organization. Please respect our volunteers' time. If a dog is listed on PetFinder, he/she IS available for adoption. We cannot reply to messages, phone calls, and emails about a dog until we have received, reviewed, and approved an adoption application. 

Our ADOPTION application is found at www.seniorhearts.org Completing this application is the first step in our adoption screening process. You MUST complete the application in entirety in order to be considered as a potential adopter.  Please select "More About Us" for further details on our adoption requirements.  You can meet a dog ONLY after we have completed our adoption approval process.

If you are looking at the dog below, it most certainly means the dog is available for adoption. We look forward to receiving your application in hopes that you are able to meet our adoption requirements and provide this dog a loving furever home.

A message from our Gigi... 

My name is Gigi. I am a 13 year young, 21 pound cocker spaniel. I can’t see and hear as well as I used to but that doesn't stop me from being a great dog.  

I like to explore in the yard and smell everything. My nose works fantastically. Walks are good if they are short and you allow us to go at my leisurely pace. 

When I want attention I will come to you and put my head on your lap for pets and rubs.  I will snuggle when I want and I will let you know. I can still be an independent girl.

I don’t mind other dogs or cats as long as they aren’t too wild and crazy. 

I can be adopted within a two-hour radius of Pittsburgh, PA. If you are interested in giving me a furever home, you must first complete the adoption application at www.seniorhearts.org

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Buddy came to us after a rescue down in Kentucky brought him to our attention.

The KY rescue became aware of Buddy's situation through a network of animal rescuers in KY. They had gotten word of a very rural home that had an overflow of dogs that needed to be rescued. They had many dogs living outside in containment shelters, most of them sort of jerry rigged kennel type things.

Apparently (and some of these facts are speculation) apparently Buddy had lived in this jerry rigged outdoor kennel (and it wasn't a tiny kennel so at least he got to move around). For possibly 8 years. It was mentioned that maybe they got him as a young dog and now he is @ 9-11 years old.

When you meet Buddy you will see how this situation would have been excruciating for him socially, as he is definitely a "Devotion Dog" He loves his person and wants to never be apart, really. He can be left of course if you go to work or aren't in the house with him, he does not have to be kenneled and will not destroy anything while you are gone and his 100% housetrained (so he doesn't have traditional separation anxiety) but you can tell when you get home and as you go about your day that this dog wants to be by your side.

Buddy also I believe is a working dog. If he is 9-11 years old he doesn't act like it. He has a drive in him, a readiness, a wanting to go. He will and can relax and lay around for hours at an end but the point is when he has an opportunity to get outside, or to go for a walk, dog park, he is "ALL IN" like he LOVES to walk and loves to explore and loves to move. Maybe he is making up for lost time of being so limited for so long. But this dog wants to go and move and do things.

And again he is as content as can be laying on dog bed near you while you work on the computer, etc. but when has chance, loves to be outside (cold and snow bother him not in the least) and he likes to just like be in the yard, and is like a guardian of the yard.

Where he is staying now the yard has chain link on one side that faces a big public park, if Buddy sees people walking by with their dogs (or just people) he will alert, with barking, he truly believes it is his duty to guard his yard. He also will sometimes bark at big vehicles like trucks going by, for some reason they stir him up.

Buddy would do best in a home with a single person. After working with him I could see him being ok with 2 people but they would both have to be super confident and savvy in understanding guardian dogs and be able to manage Buddy if he started to prefer one person over the other.

He is brilliant with one person. No issues. We did see him have 2 experiences in 2 different homes where he preferred one person over the other (the one he bonded to with the most) and then start acting like "the other" was maybe something he needed to guard against or perceived suspiciously for some reason. It was slightly random at first so we did not see this coming at all in the beginning. But we have concluded that he should go to a solo home or if two people, super savvy dog people that could work with him if he started to prefer one over the other.

It is very sad in a way because when you know Buddy you could just picture that his ideal home would have been a big family with lots of kids, a huge yard (maybe a hobby farm), lots of people, love, activity and workin' it outside. That would have been Buddy's dream.

Because he was cooped up for at least 8 years and not worked with taught anything, this may have contributed to him preferring one person and not "the other." We can only speculate.

So we are looking for "the right" home for Buddy and realize this won't be easy. But we want him to have a wonderful life full of love and activity and we do not want to set him up for failure.

Right now the best home would be a single person who loves to be active and would get Buddy out there with him/her.

Buddy 100% can be taken to the dog park-you just can't let him totally free if people are in the park "just in case" he perceived some to be a threat. He can go to the dog park with a 30 or 50 foot lead/harness and then you just gain control of him and steer him away from people if they are coming near, so you can give plenty of freedom and openness but just have ability to re-direct. I have included a video of an example of this. He basically ignores almost everyone at the dog park (not interested in the people whatsover) except will give an occasional bark if someone walking by somewhat close but doesn't lunge after them or try to go after them (Buddy is more defensive than offensive). But you just have to make sure you have control of him so you don't let people get to close to him (is the point).

Buddy LOVES walks, you can walk him with a 30 foot lead. or a regular leash, giving him plenty of exercise and freedom, you just wouldn't stop and talk to someone with him, if someone on sidewalk you steer around them. Again Buddy is way more interested in what he is smelling, you just don't want him to get defensive (of you) if someone got to close.

So dog parks, walks- absolutely yes, You just have to be his responsible manager and you can give him the best active life possible.

I could see Buddy totally living on a farm or hobby farm - IF the person had the ability to recall him when needed, teach him train him and/or had a fenced in area for him.

Buddy is good with other dogs. Buddy is "so so" not so great with cats. With an old feeble cat he was fine, with a young cat he wanted to chase.

Unfortunately no kids, even though he would adore children but because of his unpredictability can't take that chance.

Buddy is a special dog. He has suffered at the hands of well intended humans and we are looking to make up for that by giving him the most loving, and active life he can enjoy..

animal.description: Rosie is a 8 year old Vizla X Doberman mix female who is one of the most intellegent dogs you will ever meet! Rosie is a pro at tricks!  She can sit, stay, lay down, lay on her side, spin, wait, backup, get a toy on command, run or go up or down stairs on command, can stand on her hind legs, ring a bell to go out, and even more!!!  Impress your friends and always have something fun to do on snow days with smart cookie Rosie.  She wants you to know that old dogs are NEVER too old to learn even more tricks.   Fully vetted, spayed and ready to find a new home!  Due to her owners poor and declining health, Rosie was surrendered to UDR. Rosie was loved her entire life with countless hours spent by her previous owners training her, cuddling her and sharing their lives together. But we all know life can be cruel and can throw curve balls, and sadly that is what has happened. Rosie will love and snuggle you and be your constant companion throughout life. She loves all humans big and small!!! Rosie could be a therapy dog for people!!! She is a very sweet and loving dog, who absolutely loves to cuddle. This girl has impeccable house manners! She really does ring a bell to go outside. Rosie is very smart as all Dobermans are and loves training and learning new tricks. She knows how to follow behind when walking,  how to untangle her leash, lay down, lay on her side, spin, wait, back up, wait outside a doorway, get a toy on command, go upstairs or downstairs or run on command, and she knows how to stand on her hind legs. She loves feeding toys and has learned to use a game board to find treats. Rosie is very obedient and has perfected the "Stay" command, she will wait all day, you can have her sit and then scatter treats all around her and make her wait to eat them until you tell her it's OK. She excels at most basic obedience, and is very treat motivated making her training easy, all though at times she will get distracted with things and critters outside. Rosie does have a very high prey drive, is a hunter and does not do well with other dogs or cats. She will need to be the queen of her castle. Rosie adores and loves people big and small!!  Rosie will need a fully fenced yard, no exceptions, due to her high prey drive for squirrels and rabbits. If you are looking for a low maintenance companion who will love you unconditionally, Rosie is your girl! Please apply if you qualify! www.uniteddobermanrescue.org

Joy is very sweet and has a meek and mild disposition. She is pretty shy but thoroughly enjoys playing with some of the younger pups at Save A Pet. She tends to mother the others. 
Thought to be a Boxer mix, this girl weighs about 45 pounds. Multiple vets have aged her at 6 years old, but said she could be a little younger. She has had it a bit rough in the past so that can make dogs appear a little older sometimes. 
Joy never makes a mess in her kennel, so we believe that she has had some amount of house training or would be very easy to work with on house training.

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
YES we're still accepting applications for Deana. Please visit BetterDaysRescue.org and to read policies and Deana's requirements/details.

**
Deana will be placed in the Phoenix metro area, for proximity to our rescue (home checks, follow up visits, visit to finalize adoption) and for access to our veterinarian. Sorry, no exceptions.

**

Adoption begins with a Foster-To-Adopt arrangement that continues until Basic and Intermediate Obedience Training are completed. When training is complete, adoption can be finalized.

**

Deana is just adorable, full of playful energy and enthusiasm! Daily hikers, walkers, runners take note! Her coloring is exquisite and she is an athlete! Deana is elated to meet new people and wants to be friends with everyone. She bounces on to each new attraction/interaction with eager anticipation.

Deana's breed mix suggests she may have a strong prey drive, so she will not be placed with a small dog. Since she is dog-selective, she will require training before successfully integrated with another dog.

We encourage you to register on our site and "Favorite" the dog(s) that interest you, so that you will be notified when bio, photos, or status are updated.

"Companion animal" means, needs at least one other friendly, playful dog that lives full-time in the same household.
"Fenced yard" means, a backyard that is adjacent to and connected with your residence. (It does not mean a nearby fenced area/dog park.)
Gates must have padlocks and thresholds (cement or buried pavers to prevent digging.)
Yard and patio must be free of debris and have room for dogs to run and play *on a lawn and/or in a very shaded area.* Please do not invite us to your home if you have not yet landscaped your yard!
"Swimming pool" means a private, in-ground, year-round pool that is available to the dog daily or multiple times per week.
We do not place dogs in situations where there are "drained" or empty swimming pools, which are a fall hazard and contribute to the propogation of mosquitos.
Last and not least, we DO NOT adopt to students as we have found that they often do not know or anticipate where life will take them.

Discussion about a dog - including scheduling of a home check or other dialogue - cannot occur until we have received your completed adoption application. NO EXCEPTIONS. Thank you!

animal.description:
Luke is a 2 year old Lab mix that was abandoned at a property when the owner moved out and didn't take his dog with him.  The dog got some food and water from others in the neighborhood, but learned to fend for himself.  He was leery of having people approach him, so a trap was set and thankfully he went right in.  He seemed almost grateful to be back with people and it took him no time at all to allow his sweet nature to come through.  He was eaten up with fleas and his skin and coat were in horrible condition, but he is mostly healed now and ready to find his true forever home.  We will look for a fenced yard so he does not feel like he has been turned out again and always knows that he is home.

If you would like an application go to our website (https://humanesocietypc.com/) and download one and email it back as a Word or PDF document. Please no Google documents.

This dog's adoption fee is $190. That fee includes spaying/ neutering, microchipping, deworming and vaccinations.

animal.description:
This big boy is a climber and a jumper, but don't let that scare you. He's a big ole teddy bear who needs the right kind of love and attention from his forever home.
Laney loves treats and a good ear scratch from time to time along with walks, since he is a jumper, putting him outside in your backyard, you would have to constantly supervise him until he gets to know you and you all build that trust.
Please find our applications and valuable information under 'Adopt a dog'* on our website: *www.beaglesandbuddies.com* and email your application to beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Let us know your preference of appointment day/time and which dogs you are interested in and we will do our best to accommodate and email you the closest appointment available. Please allow us up to a week to get back to you. Most appointments will be Friday-Sunday, 10 am - 2 pm, for an hour.
*Note bring any other dog/s and the entire family to your meet and greet at B&B.* A complimentary training manual is included with each adoption, authored by terristeuben.com. Check out her website - she is fabulous!
B&B is glad to be open during the pandemic. We know the value and comfort of a loving pet companion and are doing our best to help the dogs and folks who need them. We update our website daily and are always rescuing, vetting, rehabilitating, socializing.
* We are accepting applications for volunteers to spend time with our dogs, hang out, sing/read to the shy ones, walk/toss ball with those who go to the playgrounds; cleaning, office work, gardening, and building/repair projects! *
Are you my furrever family?

For further info on the adoption process, please visit our home page and check out the "Adopt a Dog" section, which has thorough instructions. All our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and

fully vaccinated before adoption; they have been wormed, bathed, socialized, walked daily and much loved; each adoptee leaves with a leash, collar, and all medical records.

Our prices are higher than the shelters' because we nurse the dogs through their illnesses and get them needed surgeries and dentals. We also spend time socializing. Furthermore, unlike shelters, rescues do not get financial aid from the government and must rely on donations, grants, and adoption fees. Our fees for adults start at $150 and go up to $750. The higher end is for our most in demand dogs, such as young beagles and other purebred dogs. The lower end is for dogs who have been here a while. For puppies, we may go beyond this and charge $1000. The good news is that, because rescues fall under the "charity" category, the fees for our dogs are officially donations and are therefore tax deductible. You can think of it as donating to a worthy cause and getting a dog in return!

Sponsor Me

Beagles & Buddies must find ways to raise money so we can continue saving dogs. Your tax-deductible donation keeps our rescue kennel operating!

Hours

Friday: 10 am to 3 pm

Saturday: 10 am to 3 pm

Sunday: 10 am to 3 pm

Monday: CLOSED

Tuesday: CLOSED

Wednesday: CLOSED

Thursday: CLOSED



Weekday appointments may be available. We are a small staff and do our best to accommodate your needs. **Note that during COVID, we are not holding open houses on any day. Please email us for an appointment and include your application (found on our website, beaglesandbuddies.com, under "Forms"). Most appointments will be Friday through Sunday, though other days may also be available. We usually schedule one appointment per hour. Allow 1-2 hours for your appointment. Please look at our website and make a list of one or more dogs that you would like to see.

Contacting Us

If you have a question about adopting, giving up a dog, boarding, or volunteering, please visit the appropriate tabs on our
home page.

For more specific questions, call 626-444-9664 (please leave a voicemail if no answer) or email at beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Note that
Emailing
is always preferred!

Thanks!

Please note: If you are viewing this profile anywhere other than Beagles & Buddies own website, you are not receiving full info. Visit info on pet here.

animal.description:
Like all great celebrity couples, Bonnie & Clyde, Johnny & June, Oprah & Stedman - this adorable bonded pair has a little bit of everything. Tulip & Prince can be mischievous, entertaining and sweet all in the same day! We promise you’ll never be bored with these two around. Tulip is a senior female with a gorgeous Pyrenees coat. Prince is a younger adult Pyr mix with beautiful golden markings. These two keep each other entertained but also enjoy lots of attention from their humans. We don’t think Tulip and Prince had much training or socialization before coming to NGPR but they have made such great progress since being in their foster home. They are getting used to new people and showing less nervous behavior, also doing well with other dogs, providing there are slow introductions. They have learned their house manners at their foster home and can now sit patiently while waiting for food and treats. Now that they feel more secure at their foster home there is no more counter surfing and both are housebroken. They love lounging together in their yard, chasing squirrels, munching on hot dog slices and chewing on bones. Going on leash walks is something they love, too. They have become so much better with baths, grooming and nail trims. At the end of a long day, their favorite thing to do is snuggle up with their humans, which includes letting them squish their faces and flop all over them :) We know the Pyrfect home is out there for this dynamic duo and they promise to keep you entertained all day long!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed. 

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
Can you even believe that Ziggy has been with PAW for 1095 days! No dog should have to wait for a furever home for 3 years. Will you help him find a family to love him?

Ziggy is an active 4-year-old pup who weighs about 45 lbs. He has lots of energy and would benefit from a family who enjoys outdoor activities. Currently Ziggy lives with two other dogs, one bigger and one smaller. He does NOT need to be an only dog, he just needs the right match. Ziggy can be reactive when walking on leash and will need a patient human to help him navigate walks around the neighborhood. 

In an ideal world, Ziggy would live in a home with a large backyard and tall privacy fence so he could run to his heart's content, however that is not a deal-breaker as long as he gets plenty of exercise. Apartment/city living is probably not for Ziggy. Although an adult-only home is preferred for Ziggy, older, respectful teens may be okay. The BIGGEST thing he needs is TIME & PATIENCE to feel comfortable and confident in his new home. Doesnt he deserve that???

Ziggy doesnt always put his best paw forward when he meets new people but he bonds hard and will become a loyal best friend. He is smart, house-trained, and adorably cute. His foster mom is his biggest advocate and just wants him to find his happily ever after!!! Will that be with you?

 

To submit an adoption application go to: https://www.petstablished.com/pets/public/256884

animal.description:
Angel is a Labrador Retriever/Hound mix, born February 2019. She came to Muddy Paws with two of her puppies, Finley Rose and Huckleberry. Due to her being fearful, we recommend that there be no young children in her new home. SHE ALSO PREFERS WOMEN and it may take men a couple visits to gain her trust. Angel knows some basic commands and is mostly house-trained. She loves to play with toys and balls. She can be VERY fearful of strangers until she gets to know them, so you may need a couple visits with her to gain her trust.

Angel has had a very hard life involving possible abuse and neglect and would love a fresh start in a quieter home with patient adopters willing to help her become the best version of herself. Adopter will need to be open to working with one of our trainers free of charge.

The suggested adoption donation for Angel is $300. We are a 501c3 organization which means that your donation may be TAX DEDUCTIBLE. Your donation goes toward the high cost of veterinary care for our animals in rescue, as well as providing supportive services to animals in homes.

Information about the adoption process: All adoptions require a completed ADOPTION APPLICATION. Once your application is approved, we will put you in touch with the dogs foster to see if you and the pet are a good match. If so, we will arrange a meeting for you and the pet. The adoptions for all of our animals will take place in the Omaha, NE area and must be done by the adoptive family in person. We do not ship or deliver.

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dogs needs. If you and the dog are not a good match, we will help you select another dog, or we will keep your approved application on file for 6 months.

To learn about Muddy Paws Second Chance Rescue or donate to our animals, please visit our website at MuddyPawsSecondChanceRescue.com or our Facebook Page.

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.To speed up the adoption process, please complete our Pre-Adoption Application.Spud is a very energetic loving boy! He loves to run and play with other dogs, or just by himself, and is pretty good at fetch. He loves to cuddle and will climb right up into your lap. He does well with kids but forgets how big he is sometimes. He is very vocal and isn't a fan of people leaving, but he calms down pretty quickly. He does well in the car, he's house trained, he knows how to sit, but isn't a fan of cats. Would do best in a house with older kids and I am good with dogs that are simular in size.Prior to adoption I will be altered, vaccinated, health checked, dewormed, and micro-chipped.
Adoption Fee $250 +taxes/feesIf you would like to meet me please fill out a pre-adoption application at www.tailsrescue.orgHappy Tails Adoption Center is open on Sundays from 12-5pm. We are located at 7940 University Ave NE, Fridley. Dogs are at events based on the availability of their foster family. Please fill out a pre-adoption application so we know you are interested in meeting/adopting one of our animals. The breeds of our dogs and cats are a 'best guess.' We often do not know what mix they are and have to base it on what we think they look like, and base it on breeds often found in the area they came from. Most of our dogs who have gotten DNA tests done are 4-10 breeds mixed together. Because their breed mix is a guess we cannot guarantee a 'full grown size' of many of our younger animals.Interested in adopting me? Click here to fill out an application!Happy Tails Rescue Minnesota is located at 7940 University Ave NE, Fridley MN 55432. We are open for adoption events from 12-5 every Sunday. If there is a certain animal you want to meet at one the events please fill out a preadoption application to directly contact their foster family or check our Facebook page to see if they will be there! Their event attendance is based on the availability of their foster family.
Home visits (video tours or in person) are required for all dog adoptions. All of our cats and dogs are INDOOR pets and are NOT to be left outside unattended (even in a fenced yard), or running loose!
