Our dogs are split between residence at our shelter, Camp Pawsawhile Retreat, and foster homes. Meet and greets are available by appointment only. Please complete an adopter profile to set up your meet and greet: http://coastalpetrescue.org/adopt/profile

Adoption Fees:
Kittens: $60, Cats (1 year plus): $50, Puppies: $250, Adult Canines (1 to 6 years): $200, Seniors (7 years plus): $100 (unless otherwise specified). Adoption fees are not a tax-deductible donation as allowed by IRS regulations. Adoption fees help to offset the cost of the pet's care incurred by Coastal Pet Rescue, which are generally 2 to 3 times the adoption fee amount.
Some special circumstances may change the fee; see pet's listing for actual adoption fee.

All Coastal Pet Rescue pets are current on shots, microchipped* and spayed/neutered prior to adoption. Adopters are responsible for any shots that may be due after adoption (particularly for kittens and puppies that must have three rounds of shots to be protected).

Microchip:
CPR has implanted a microchip as part of the adoption process and the chip is included in the adoption fee. However, some chip companies require a registration fee varying from $9.99 to $19.99. The registration fees are the responsibility of the adopter and are NOT included in the CPR adoption fee. Adopters may add this cost to their adoption fee to have CPR register the chip on their behalf.

30 Days Pet Insurance: 
As a Petfinder member, all adopters are entitled to a free 30 day insurance policy through PetFirst. Coastal Pet Rescue is not responsible for this policy. Adopters must call PetFirst’s toll-free number 855-710-7387 to activate the coverage. If adopters fail to call, the policy will not be activated.

Personality Type: Playful, Loyal, Sensitive, Cautious, Snuggly!
History: Owner surrender

Special Info: Familiar with living in a home, housebroken, obedience trained, loves to go for walks, play fetch, and snuggle under blankets. Comes with a care package of all of his favorite things as well as one free training session with our trainer!

The information we are providing for this animal was developed based on observations and assessments in a shelter or foster environment. We do our best to provide information that will help determine if the dog might be a good fit for you. Please note that behaviors may change in a home environment. We also ask our applicants to assume that any animal they adopt from us will need to be potty trained and learn house manners, although this is not always the case. Our online animal bios are designed to provide as much information as possible and answer some anticipated questions. We do not have the resources to respond to emails with more specific questions.

We are receiving an unusually high number of applications per pet at this time! Please follow the rules below to ensure your application is reviewed; pay attention closely to these instructions because applications will NOT be processed if they are not followed. Please keep in mind that dog/cat availability is currently changing by the hour; you will receive an email if the animal you are interested in is no longer available. New dogs become available almost every day, so feel free to let us know if someone else interests you if your initial choice is already adopted! 

Fill out the application (DOG: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/IHD-DOG-Application-9-10-18.pdf, CAT: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/IHD-CAT-Application.pdf) completely. Every question must be answered, and it must be signed. If you are going to type your responses, open the application, save it, type your answers, and save it again. 

-Applicants must be 21+ years old and live within a 50-mile radius of our shelter at 22415 Groesbeck Hwy, Warren 48089.

-You must identify at least 1 dog/cat that you are interested in. If there are multiple dogs/cats, number them in order of priority. 

-Scan a copy of proof of home ownership (i.e. tax bill, deed, or mortgage payment - you can black out the account #, etc.) or animal clause/agreement of your rental agreement.

-Attach the application and home ownership proof/rental agreement animal clause to a new email and send it to bark@iheartdogs.org. The subject line must be formatted to read ""#1 choice of dog/cat, Your First and Last Name"". Example: Subject: Fido, Jane Doe
Once your application is received, it will be assigned to an Adoption Counselor who will follow-up with the applicant who is the best fit within a few days, or to discuss other dogs/cats. It could take up to a couple of weeks for you to receive a final disposition on your application so there is no need to check on the status.

-Introductions will be scheduled by appointment only, 45 minutes per appointment. The entire household, including current dogs, must be present for the appointment. The introductions will take place outside in our parking lot.

-We will continue to perform vet checks for current and prior pets in the household.

-Home visits will be in person for the yard and virtual for inside the home.

-Finalizing the adoption will also be scheduled by appointment.

While this process may seem cumbersome, it is interim during COVID-19, and it is designed to help us respond to the volume of emails we receive every day. Since we are receiving a high volume of applications, please be patient if a dog/cat is no longer available. 

Thank you for your understanding.

animal.description:
Meet Duncan!!

Duncan is a 2-3-year-old bully mix who is originally from South Carolina. He came to MA as a young puppy but his owners were unable to keep him. We were asked to help find him a new home and we couldn’t say no to this boy. We strongly feel that Duncan had a very rough time with his first family and his very formative years were spent without the proper amount of exercise, socialization, and training.

Duncan shows a strong bond to those he trusts and we feel he deserves to find a family who will show him what true love means. Since coming to us Duncan has been working very hard to get his exercise and to learn to be a good boy. He has come so far with the help of Boston Dogtor.

Due to Duncan's needs, we want to make sure that he finds the perfect family and it's a great match from day one. Boston Dogtor has graciously agreed to meet with Duncan's adopters to teach them the proper handling technique and show them the skills Duncan has learned. 

We do think Duncan would do well in a home with a confident female dog. 

If you are interested in adopting Duncan, please visit our website to fill out an application! 
www.safewithusanimalrescue.org

animal.description:
Remo is a 2 year old pittie mix.  This big sexy beast had a rather rocky start in life.  His foster mom has literally luved him back to life. He is still a bit skittish & protective over his food so his perfect family will be one who understands rescue dogs and has patience to help Remo continue to learn how to be a playful pup.  He loves cuddles and playing with the cats. He is leash and kennel trained    He sleeps mostly in the bed with his foster family so he’s a great snuggle partner.  Remo just needs his furever family to find him soon so he can start growing as a part of the family.   Like most rescue pups, this furbaby is HW+, but is currently undergoing the *slow-kill method of treatment (see more information below).  

All our adoption fees include spay/neuter, micro-chip, up-to-date vaccinations, including rabies thru date of adoption. This pup is heartworm positive and is currently being treated with the *slow kill method, approved by her veterinarian, on prevention & on flea/tick prevention. 

*The slow kill method of treatment, simply stated, is a 30 day regiment of  doxycycline followed by a monthly dose of Advantage Multi for 12 months, then retesting.   Most dogs test negative after one year of following this treatment; however, we always recommend that potential adopters consult & follow the advice of their family veterinarian upon adopting any of our hw+ pups.   Although the fast-kill method is still considered the "gold-standard" by the AVA, and may be preferred by some vets; the slow-kill method has proven to be effective in our rescue. The main reason we utilize this method is due to our limited financial constraints and the high number of our rescue pups that are infected.   In the cases of severe infection and if the pup is highly symptomatic, we sometimes use the fast-kill approach instead.   Again, we recommend for you to consult with your veterinarian after the adoption is complete and follow their recommendations.   

In order to be considered for one of our beautiful pups, please go to our website and complete and application: https://www.mustluvdogs.org/adoptable-pets.
Please note that we are a DUE DILIGENCE adoption organization. Part of our approval process requires, among other things:
* Experienced pet home with verifiable vet references/history preferred, but we realize that everyone has to start somewhere, so all applications will be considered.
*The majority, but not all, of our pets require a fenced yard or secure enclosure.  In the case of apartments, we require Landlord approval and designated dog area in complex.
*Verifiable good veterinary history INCLUDING regular vaccination/visits and good Heartworm Prevention history is a MUST!
*Adopter must be able to have time to spend with the pup and be able to provide the pup a safe environment to live.
*ALL our dogs are expected to be primarily INSIDE dogs.  They MUST sleep inside the home.  We truly understand that some folks have working dogs (i.e. farmers, ranchers,etc); however, the majority of our dogs have had a rough life prior to coming to us & we want to make sure that they are showered with LUV & maybe even a bit spoiled for the rest of their lives. 

Other facts are also considered, including whether children or other pets are a good fit with the dog. 

Must Luv Dogs reserves the right to deny any applications that we don't think are a good fit with the pup. Our first & foremost concern is the dog's best interest. It is our MISSION to place them in a home that is a great fit for their needs for a lifetime of luv & being part of a family.
*We will consider adoptions in any area; however, will do not ship or transport puppies under the age of 12 mos. We will ONLY transport an adult dog on a transport approved by MLD, at adopter's expense.
* In order to be affordable and afford every family an opportunity to have a pup of their own, we keep our Adoption Fees low; however, please keep in mind that the fees we charge do not cover all costs for the pup.  Any additional donations are greatly appreciated!

Please note that all of our pets are in private foster homes. In order to reduce any stress or confusion for our pups, we require a completed, approved application BEFORE setting up a meet & greet for any of our pups.  Alternatively, you are always welcome to come meet any of our pups at one of our regular Adoption Events.   Our events are always posted on PetFinder OR on our Facebook page: https://www.facebook.com/mustLUVdogs.org.

Finally, THANK YOU for considering Must Luv Dogs for your next pet. 

*Most dogs require a fenced area in yard. 
*Apartments okay IF nearby dog park or walking trails (with landlord appoval).
*ALL dogs must be INSIDE dogs and treated a part of family. 
*We are a DUE DILIGENCE Adoption Rescue.  
*Must have good Vet history & Heartworm prevention is a MUST!
*ALL dogs are fully vetted, spay/neutered and microchipped prior to adoption.

animal.description:
“Ohana means family. Family means nobody gets left behind or forgotten.”

Maggie is a 5 year old, sweet and loving tripod who weighs around 55 pounds. From becoming a tripod as a puppy, rupturing her cruciate ligament, and a long journey to recover from that, Maggie has had quite the rollercoaster of a life. She is ready to put these events behind her, and join a furever family that will love her as much as she loves them. We cannot believe that this sweet girl hasn’t gotten snatched up yet because she is about as sweet as they come!

Maggie is completely crate-trained and housebroken, but she can be trusted to have free rein in the house. If left out in the house while you’re away, Maggie will just snooze the day away on the couch until her person comes home. Maggie knows “sit,” “stay,” and “down.” She’s working on learning “focus” to redirect her attention to her Foster Mom when she gets distracted.

Maggie has such an optimistic view of the world and absolutely adores every person that comes her way. Some might expect her to be a wary or nervous dog, but she’s completely trusting of people. She sees strangers as the best friends she hasn’t met yet, and she’s ready to share her love of life with everyone. Foster Mom says she has a personality so sweet that it’s infectious to everyone she meets. She is the type of dog who will love you unconditionally: she gets whole-body wiggles every time that her person walks through the door. 

Maggie needs a home where she is the only resident animal - she’s got enough love for everybody! She’s not a big fan of cats, but we are happy to share that Maggie is getting good with her dog etiquette! She’s attended doggy charm school and has worked with a trainer to help her relate to other dogs. Even though she is a typical talkative pitty, she’s learning how to appropriately engage in play and has enjoyed many playdates with other friendly ACR dogs! She loves to run back and forth with dogs along the fence and is enjoying what it means to have canine pals!

Currently Maggie is happy with a couple good walks a day, but she loves to get to run around! She is a HUGE fan of getting to run in large spaces, and she lights up when she sees a big fenced-in area where she can really see how fast those three legs can take her -- and that’s pretty fast! Ms. Maggie loves to play tug-of-war with anyone up for the challenge, but she can also entertain herself with some of her favorite toys: Kongs with treats and peanut butter stuffed inside are some of her favorites! 

Maggie has a huge personality with brains to boot, and she knows how to communicate what she needs with her people.  If she catches you looking at her, she’ll probably wiggle over to you to ask for some butt scratches and belly rubs! If she could have her way, she’d cuddle up close to someone all day long. When she gets super cozy, she spreads out to take up as much room on the couch as she can, and her foster mom just doesn’t have the heart to move her when she’s so peaceful! When she is, you’ll know as soon as she’s drifted off to sleep because our girl is not the most delicate snoozer: she’s got quite the powerful snore!

Maggie has been waiting so long because she knows the perfect family is out there for her and is waiting with open arms. Could it be yours? Contact us today, she can’t wait to meet you!


If you’d like to be considered to adopt, the first step in the process is to submit an application through our website: http://athenscaninerescue.com/adoption-procedures/. Our adoption fee is $250 per dog over the age of 6 months and $300 per dog 6 months or younger. We accept payment by Venmo, PayPal, or card.

This includes: basic vet care (i.e. basic vaccinations, including boosters completed after adoption, spay/neuter, heartworm/flea preventatives, and treatment for any health needs while in our care), a microchip, a week’s worth of food for the trial-period, and a harness lead.

We typically adopt to homes within 30 minutes of Athens, GA, as we require a basic home check to ensure all dogs are placed in a safe environment. If you are further away than that and are interested in one of our pups, please still fill out an application and we can discuss your options. 

We do not have a facility and operate through a network of foster homes. Thus, we do not have a phone number. If you’d like to discuss potential adoptions, please email at adopt@athenscaninerescue.com.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Interested in adopting? See our adoption proccess.
*** Adoption Pending***

SILVER is from a really sad situation where she was left on their own for at least two years at a construction site. Food and water were not always available, and she sought shelter and shade under a variety of construction vehicles. Silver came into rescue and was given a thorough vet exam and much needed bath and grooming! While the volunteers were at first timid about interacting with these "wild" pups, Silver soon won them over! She is gentle, loves attention and easy to walk on leash. Very chill and laid back this pup deserves a place to call home where she can be spoiled, and she can get all the love she has missed out on. She can be uncertain and protective around other dogs so would love to be in a home without other pups and definitely no cats. She loves kids and seems to actually prefer kids to adults according to our volunteers who brought their children out for dog socialization. This pup is quite food driven but needs to lose a few pounds so a healthy diet will help her out immensely.

Looking for that chill, loving older Mal? Silver could be your girl!!
Interested in sponsoring? See our sponsorship information.

animal.description:
Hi meet Mork,

Mork is a Lovely Pitty mix who is about 5 years old and is full grown at around 60lbs. Mork loves playing with other dogs and toys but is also an amazing snuggler. He is a tad shy around strangers at first but the moment he warms up, he will show you how amazing he really is. Mork wants a person/family who will provide him with a life of mental and physical stimulation while keeping him safe and happy. He loves to be with his people, so he needs a plan if there are longer workdays, so he is not spending too much time in a crate.

Mork came to us after being rescued from the shelter system.

We hold an event every weekend at our facility on SATURDAY 11-5pm.   Please visit our social media platforms for the specifics for each weekend as it changes from week to week. Please find our application at lovejoyfoundation.org when you come to an event please bring that filled out in hand with you. You can find our application at Lovejoyfoundation.orgYou MUST submit an APPLICATION via email in hopes to get an appointment, our application is found on our website lovejoyfoundation.org. If you do not get a phone call by Friday then we did not have anything available for you or the pet of interest was adopted before we got you application. We are a Southern California based rescue and do nothing adopt further than an hour from our headquarters in Inglewood, Ca. we do not adopt out more than a 30 minute radius. We appreciate you being understanding and Patient as we attempt to go back to a new normal.

animal.description:
****Please do not send us inquiries/emails asking if a dog is still available; if a dog is still listed on Petfinder, we are still accepting applications for them. See the bottom of this bio for more FAQs regarding our adoption process before emailing.****

ABOUT VENUS:

Venus arrived at SNARR's adoption center with a freshly amputated hind leg and a very guarded demeanor. However, once she got the hang of walking on 3 legs and had some time to decompress, her awesome personality shined through! 

Despite being a tripod, Venus is still very strong and will require an experienced dog owner who will be able to handle her strength! She will likely need quiet time to decompress in a new home once adopted, so we do recommend she goes to a more low-key household without small children.
*Venus is not comfortable around men and will require a female adopter.*

Venus is up to date on vaccinations and has been spayed and microchipped.

If you are interested in fostering or adopting Venus, please go to www.snarrnortheast.org/applications and fill out an application.

-------------------------------------------------------
FAQs -- PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING

**Please note that SNARR NE is a volunteer-based organization. While our volunteers will try to respond to you as quickly as possible, it is helpful if you review the following information about our adoption process before emailing:**

- LISTED BREED(S) & AGE: We are taking our best guess on age, breed, and size when fully grown, based on the puppy's/dog's physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. *NOTE* We rarely know a dog's exact age, nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. Because we often do not have access to medical records at the time that we are posting dogs to Petfinder, so there are sometimes discrepancies between what is posted on Petfinder and what might be listed on a dog's medical records.

- SNARR'S ADOPTION PROCESS: The first step in adopting or meeting a SNARR dog/puppy is to fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. Once we receive your application, one of our adoption application processors will contact you, review our adoption process with you, and answer any additional questions you may have. **We do not go on a first-come-first-serve basis for adoptions, but on best fit for a family and most importantly the puppy or dog.**

- MEETING ADOPTABLE DOGS: Meet and greets will not be scheduled until after your adoption application has been fully processed by one of our adoption processors.

- APPLYING ONLINE: If you fill out an online application, please do so from a computer (not a mobile device), make sure you answer ALL the questions in as much detail as possible, and that you receive a confirmation email. If you do not receive a confirmation email, that means we did NOT receive your application.

- PUPPIES: We do suggest listing a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several litter mates.

- ADOPTION FEES:  $495 for puppies / $375 for adults / Adoption Fees for Seniors, Special Needs and Bonded Pairs vary

animal.description:
Brewer is a handsome and loyal Greater Swiss Mountain dog mix who loves his toys and dotes on his humans. He gets very tuned in to his people, has good house manners and is highly food motivated. Quick to learn, he already knows a few commands (sit, paw, down). 
Smaller than a standard Swissie, Brewer is fully grown at about 85 lbs. He is an adult (The NY vet estimates him at 5-6), and has a medium energy level. Regular exercise is excellent for him, but mountain hikes or dog park play would not be ideal as he has arthritis in his hips (which is managed with medication). Brewer has doggie friends, but can sometimes be intimidated by larger male dogs (Brewer isn’t a cat person). Although he loves his toys and treats, he isn’t always good at sharing, so would thrive in an adult home or a home with older children. 
This handsome guy does not ask for a lot. He would love a life where he can be with his people most of the time, play with his toys, sleep on a soft doggy bed and go for happy regular walks. 

Brewer is up to date on vaccinations and has been dewormed, neutered and microchipped.

****Please do not send us inquiries/emails asking if a dog is still available; if a dog is still listed on Petfinder, we are still accepting applications for them. See the bottom of this bio for more FAQs regarding our adoption process before emailing.****

MEET NAVYA: the great adventurer, the wheelchair queen, and the star of her neighborhood back in India. 

Navya was rescued in India after being found on the highway, dragging herself with cars zipping by her a hundred miles an hour. A kind gentleman got her out of harm's way, but not before her poor feet were crushed by a car. Once rescued, she was flown into Chicago, and then transported from Chicago to Texas. Now she is waiting to make her New York debut where she hopes to find her forever home!

Navya is such a trooper and has really come a long way! She uses her wheelchair like a champ, and has even gone to the beach in her wheels! And guess what? She LOVED IT!

There seems to be some potential for her to use her back legs again someday; you can see her try to use them at times while in her cart. SNARR is able to provide amazing physical therapy for her in NY (our PT foster is in Armonk) if we can find a foster or adopter for this sweet girl.

To apply to foster or adopt Navya, go to www.snarrnortheast.org/applications and fill out an application.

-------------------------------------------------------
FAQs -- PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING

**Please note that SNARR NE is a volunteer-based organization. While our volunteers will try to respond to you as quickly as possible, it is helpful if you review the following information about our adoption process before emailing:**

- LISTED BREED(S) & AGE: We are taking our best guess on age, breed, and size when fully grown, based on the puppy's/dog's physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. *NOTE* We rarely know a dog's exact age, nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. Because we often do not have access to medical records at the time that we are posting dogs to Petfinder, so there are sometimes discrepancies between what is posted on Petfinder and what might be listed on a dog's medical records.

- SNARR'S ADOPTION PROCESS: The first step in adopting or meeting a SNARR dog/puppy is to fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. Once we receive your application, one of our adoption application processors will contact you, review our adoption process with you, and answer any additional questions you may have. **We do not go on a first-come-first-serve basis for adoptions, but on best fit for a family and most importantly the puppy or dog.**

- MEETING ADOPTABLE DOGS: Meet and greets will not be scheduled until after your adoption application has been fully processed by one of our adoption processors.

- APPLYING ONLINE: If you fill out an online application, please do so from a computer (not a mobile device), make sure you answer ALL the questions in as much detail as possible, and that you receive a confirmation email. If you do not receive a confirmation email, that means we did NOT receive your application.

- PUPPIES: We do suggest listing a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several litter mates.

animal.description:
Hi meet Chance,

Chance is a Lovely American Bulldog mix who is about 6 years old and is full grown at around 70lbs. Chance loves playing with his humans and toys but is also an amazing snuggler. He is a tad shy around strangers at first but the moment he warms up, he will show you how amazing he really is. He would be best as an only dog in the home as he LOVES to get all the attention. Chance wants a person/family who will provide him with a life of mental and physical stimulation while keeping him safe and happy. He loves to be with his people, so he needs a plan if there are longer workdays, so he is not spending too much time in a crate. He would make a wonderful hiking, running, or walking partner.

Chance came to us after being rescued from the shelter system. The independent fellow rescuer that pulled him and Allie wanted to give them a second opportunity to find their forever homes, but they fell ill and needed help, they reached out to TLF for assistance.

We hold an event every weekend at our facility on SATURDAY 11-5pm.   Please visit our social media platforms for the specifics for each weekend as it changes from week to week. Please find our application at lovejoyfoundation.org when you come to an event please bring that filled out in hand with you. You can find our application at Lovejoyfoundation.orgYou MUST submit an APPLICATION via email in hopes to get an appointment, our application is found on our website lovejoyfoundation.org. If you do not get a phone call by Friday then we did not have anything available for you or the pet of interest was adopted before we got you application. We are a Southern California based rescue and do nothing adopt further than an hour from our headquarters in Inglewood, Ca. we do not adopt out more than a 30 minute radius. We appreciate you being understanding and Patient as we attempt to go back to a new normal.

animal.description:
Puppernickel is a 14 week old Great Pyrenees puppy that was unfortunately mauled by another dog at her property when she was only 3 weeks old. After a few weeks she was thankfully surrendered to a vet clinic and they reached out to us to help get her the proper care Puppernickel has seen a neurologist and while there is evidence of cervical spine trauma and remodeling, she also suffers from deformities of her thoracic spine and there is sadly no surgical intervention that will help her be able to walk again without a wheelchair. She is a very sweet girl who is good with everyone and everything that she meets. She tries her best to do all the things she wants to do and now she has her wheels she is enjoying being mobile once again!

Giant Breed Experienced Homes Only.

BDHPI Puppy Policy

All puppies less than 6 months of age are too young to be spayed/neutered so they are adopted out on special puppy spay/neuter agreements with a $50 refundable spay/neuter deposit. Adopting families must agree to get the puppy altered within 2 weeks of 6 months of age and send proof of S/N to BDHPI accordingly. Adopting families are expected to make a donation of $425 minimum for mixed puppies AND will have the additional costs listed above, so please keep this in mind.

When adopting a puppy, new families need to be prepared for not only a substantial financial investment, but also a significant time commitment in order to raise your puppy properly. Crate training is a critical part of setting them up for success as well as potty training. You can't leave a puppy in the crate for longer than 4 hours max and they typically have to be let outside every hour when you are home since their bladder is not as big as an adult. You will want to make sure your puppy gets regular exercise and has plenty of mentally stimulating chew toys such as puzzle toys(food cubes, busy buddy toys, kongs, etc). Socialization the first 6 months is critical to their development socially and once they have had all of their shots, you will want to take your new puppy everywhere you can to get them used to meeting lots of new people, different dogs, and visiting places outside of the home. Obedience training is also extremely important (and actually part of our adoption agreement requirements) so that your puppy grows up to be a gentle giant instead of a giant monster!

To see the most up to date adoption status of this dog, please visit www.bigdogshugepaws.com
This is just one of hundreds of gentle giants available for adoption at BDHPI! It is best not to get your heart set on any one particular dog upfront because there is no guarantee they will still be available once you are approved or that they are even the right match for your family. Purebred puppies are only eligible for adoption to giant breed experienced homes.

animal.description:
Hiya,

My name is Presley, you know like "The King of Rock-n-Roll" Presley??  Yeah, I'm almost as famous and awesome as that!

So my story is a sad one.  While one of the volunteers was speaking with a police officer about another matter, she had mentioned that she had been keeping an eye on a doggie that had been chained to a dog house and bred over and over and over again.  Before the officer could help it, the doggie had disappeared.  She had looked everywhere for it, to no avail.

The lady at Lucies compared photos of me and the dog the officer was talking about, and they believed me to be the same dog!  You see, I was believed to have been chained and bred over and over and over.  I had arrived at Lucies shortly before they had this conversation.  Amazing right?

It's so nice to know that there are police officers out there that care as much about us pets as they do humans.  To protect and serve...she did that alright!!

The nice peeps here took me in and cared, loved and trained me.  I'm now a happy, well cared for doggie :)  I could possibly be a great watchdog, as I am very alert.

I so enjoy playing in the water and fetching balls!

What I would really enjoy though, is having a family that would give me the love and attention I deserve after all I have been through.  Could you be that family???

*** We strive to ensure our dogs are going to a safe, loving and caring home. Phone interviews are required for all adoptions****

Online Adoption Application 
Here at PMR we **love** a good hound dog. Copper is wonderful and won't disappoint. This handsome boy came to us as an owner surrender after the other dog in the home didn't accept him. It wasn't his fault!

Copper can be aloof at first-- he is still a 'puppy brain' and trying to figure where he belongs in the world. Especially in new settings, there are so many great things to smell that he might get busy exploring his environment. He does pull hard on a leash. But once he settles in, he is just the sweetest baby who wants to cuddle, play, snuggle on the couch, and be your best friend.

He loves other dogs and dog parks even more. He has a a lot of energy and some older dogs might not appreciate his exuberance. We also don't recommend young kids because he may jump on them-- he needs to learn manners. He is potty trained and loves playing in the yard-- a fenced yard would be the best for him.

Copper does not, however, enjoy car rides. He becomes very scared and just howls-- "what is this insane contraption?" he says and "why is the ground moving?"

This sweetie is just waiting for someone to give him a chance.

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in dog who needs a new home. Adoption can be one of the most fulfilling experiences in your life and especially in the life of your new canine companion.

A note to those looking at CPR. We have no perfect dogs - but many of our dogs have proven to be perfect for a certain someone. Our job is to find those someone's. Our most successful adopters come to CPR not because they want a dog. They come to us because they want to give a dog a home. We urge all of our potential adopters not to fall in love with a picture. While we like to know what you like in looks, a dog is more than a pretty face. Our goal is to match you with the best possible pet for you and your home. We want to create furever families.

Our descriptions contain all that we know about this dog today. We'll update as more information is known.

Are you looking to adopt within the next 30 days? If so please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and complete the application. You'll find it in the menu on the left hand side. You'll also find a total listing of all our dogs available.

Just browsing but interested in poodles and poodle mixes? Please drop a note to applications@carolinapoodlerescue.org with your name, address and phone # and email. We'll add you to our mailing list.

thanks
the CPR Adoption team

Date into Rescue: 8/1/2020
Reason for being in rescue: Rocky was surrendered by his owners to a rural shelter. Carolina Poodle Rescue pulled him from the shelter.
Foster location: Dreamweaver Farms, Pacolet SC
Special Needs? Rocky had surgery on 8/14/20 to remove a retained testicle that was cancerous. He also had a dental and lost 4 teeth. Rocky is a bit underweight. He also has hair loss and itchy skin from suspected flea allergies.
Weight: 19 lbs. Rocky should weigh at least 25 lbs.
Height: 14 in
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $1 - I am priceless

Fence needed? No

What kind of home would be best for me? Rocky is a little like a sour-patch kid - he is equal parts sweet and sour. He needs an experienced owner that is comfortable allowing Rocky to live on his terms. He is not a dog that you can pick up - he will snap at you. Rocky needs a quiet, low-traffic home where he can retire. He would prefer to be the only dog, but could live with other animals. Rocky will not be placed in a home with children; he will snap at them.

What is my personality like? Rocky is a senior guy who likes what he likes and doesn't like what he doesn't like. All things are on his terms. He is a quiet boy who prefers to spend most of his days relaxing in his crate on a soft bed with the door open. This allows him the freedom to come and go as he prefers, on his terms. Rocky loves food and he will work for food when he is in the mood. You just have to remember that he can go from very loving to spicy in a matter of seconds. When Rocky is not in the mood or doesn't want to do something, he will try to bite.

Rocky is an independent soul. He doesn't mind other dogs, but really prefers being alone. He is indifferent to cats, primarily ignoring their presence. He walks well on a leash and will follow your voice. His favorite things are fuzzy beds and quiet space.

How do I act when I first meet new people? Aloof and quiet

Other tips and tidbits: Rocky's estimated birthday is 7/31/2007

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

Please note - we do not ship dogs. If you are interested in adopting, please take a look at the distance between the foster home location and your location and make sure you are willing to make that trip. Most of our dogs are at our farm in Pacolet, South Carolina.

To apply, please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and visit the tab on the left that directions you to the online application.

Please note that when screening applications, we look at the entire home and then make suggestions based on what would be a good fit for your home. You are not being screened for a specific dog although we are looking to see what type of dog interests you - poodles or non poodles, color, age, etc. Others here may be a better fit for you. It is very difficult to get to know a living animal from a picture and a short description. Since we are constantly getting in new dogs, this may be a dog not in our listings yet. We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.

animal.description:
Please contact Jamesa (roxysrescue@yahoo.com), 713-882-2610 for more information about this pet.Try A Tripod!Lady Faith has the softest kisses I have had from a dog, she gives just a quiet peck that barely touches you and she only does it when she wants something.
Meet my senior tripod girl who I happen to think is the best! I did not check the 'special needs' box because she has no special needs. Yes, she only has 3 legs but that is not a special need or a disability. She gets around just fine. She does not climb the stairs but she can jump off of the deck and climb her way back up. She is maintenance free, she requires nothing extra other than love and head scratches.
Lady Faith was found on the side of the road after being hit by a car. The break was so bad she needed to have her back left leg amputated. She is up to date on vaccinations, rabies, already spayed, heartworm negative and microchipped.
This young lady (vet estimates her to be 8 years old) is kind and gentle, she loves dogs of all sizes. She is already completely house trained and can be totally trusted to be left alone in the home while you are gone. She is also crate trained. She will go to the door when she has to potty but if you do not see her she will come and get you. She has perfect house manners.
If you want a very loving companion, Lady Faith is your lady! She has manners, she loves treats and she loves to be loved. No barking, sometimes she will talk to you if you talk to her! Her personality is what you are looking for if you want a cozy companion. She weighs 62 lbs and does not shed. She walks well on a leash, enjoys a car ride and just hanging out with you no matter what it is.
Transportation is available across the United States.
ADOPTION FEE & APPLICATION REQUIRED

Roxy's K-9 Rescue does not have a shelter, all of our dogs are raised in foster homes. Each dog comes spay/neutered (fixed), rabies shots appropriate for their age, and dewormed twice. The dogs are up to date on vaccinations according to their age at the time of adoption. They are microchipped, heartworm tested and on monthly flea/tick and heartworm preventative. ALL OF THIS IS INCLUDED IN THE ADOPTION FEE.
Medical records will come with each dog at the time of adoption.
Our organization is run by volunteers/foster parents, please be patient to give us time to respond to your emails and/or phone calls. We will reply to you. Thank you.

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting Tony, please email jimmy.he@lostdogrescue.org.

Tony is a dog on a mission. A mission to find his one and only human that is! Tony still has all the boundless energy and curiosity of a young puppy, but the list of ways to appreciate him is simple ... Throw ball. Admire adorableness as he runs. Take wet ball from mouth. Rinse and repeat. See? That's not too much to ask right?

Tony would love to find an experienced adult companion living the single life who will take him on walks, jogs, and hikes to explore his world. He came to us from Iran as a young puppy, so he is still adjusting to all the sights, smells, and sounds of his new surroundings, but he loves the outdoors and stopping to smell all the roses. His love for toys and treats is unconditional and he'll let you pet him for as long as your hands are willing and able. Tony is wise beyond his years and has an insatiable thirst for training. He already knows sit, down, wait, shake, leave it, and has a pretty good heel too! Not bad for a 1 year old, right? As the old saying goes, practice makes perfect, so he will need someone with the time, patience, and dedication to continue reinforcing his obedience training. Tony takes some time to warm up to new people, but once he gets comfortable, watch out! He is quite the attention hog and quickly bonds with one person so he would love to find that special someone to be his designated sidekick. Tony is also working diligently on his dog manners and containing his excitement when seeing other dogs on walks. He has been attending weekly group walks and hikes with other dogs and has shown tremendous improvement around his furry friends. A fenced-in backyard to run, play fetch, and release all his puppy zoomies is on his wish list too! Tony is already house-broken and sleeps through the night without incident. He told us that his requirements are quite modest: an experienced and single-occupancy owner who will shower him with endless love and plenty of training (you), a warm spot to rest on (your lap), and cozy accommodations (your home). So, do you fit the bill? If yes, come meet Tony today and bring some love, laughs, and licks into your life!

Estimated DOB: 5/11/2019

Sponsored by Brian McNeill

The owner recently lost their home and was unable to keep the boys and sadly they landed on the EUTH list at the Wichita Animal Shelter and needed pulled by a rescue. animal.description:
This strikingly gorgeous boy with two different-colored eyes is Glacier. This boy came into rescue being found with a gunshot wound - he has since been treated and has recovered well, and he is more than eager to find a furever home of his own! Despite this traumatic event, Glacier is the sweetest and kindest boy. He gets along wonderfully with his foster sibling, and he is always eager to meet new friends. He is exceptionally calm and gentle around children, and he simply adores everyone who wants to meet him. Glacier's current favorite activity is getting belly rubs - he will come up in front of you, roll over on his belly, practically begging for a belly rub :) Glacier is not a big fan of car rides or thunderstorms, but a good chunk of cheese can usually help him get over it. This sweet, gentle boy has such a lovely temperament that it is hard not to fall in love with him. He is so eager to love that he will happily lie by your side until you have time to play with him. Will you be the one to show Glacier that there is plenty of love around for him too?

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed.

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
Name: Slim Jim
Age: 8 years
Weight: 12 pounds
Sex/Spayed: Male, neutered
Coat: Smooth
Color: Black and Tan
Energy Level: Low - Medium
Adoption Fee: $200
Contact: leighjrice@yahoo.com

*******READY FOR ADOPTION******
*******SPECIAL NEEDS********
*******AWESOME PUP********
*******PLEASE READ THE ENTIRE BIO****** 
UPDATED 1/24/21

Slim Jim was found as a stray and placed into rescue in August 2020.  In the last 6 months, he has been on medical hold due to being heartworm positive and also because he has seizures.  He received his last treatment for heartworms at the beginning of Jan.  We don't anticipate that he will need anything other than monthly preventatives in the future related to the heartworms.

Slim has been treated and monitored very closely for his seizures.  His seizures were well controlled for almost three months but he has had some breakthrough seizures in the month.  He comes out of his seizures well, and generally gets back to normal within 10-15 minutes.  Any potential adopter will have to understand that he will have ongoing needs for vet care and medication related to his seizures.  It would be ideal if he could be followed by his current vet in FWB to ensure continuity in his care.  This will be a consideration when choosing a home for him.  

He is currently on a medication that has to be given every 8 hours so he will need to be in a home with adopters who can accommodate his needs.  He is on Phenobarbital and Keppra at this time.  The estimated cost of these two scripts will be around $40 a month.  Slim  takes his medicine easily with the help of pill pockets and peanut butter.  

In return for your dedication to his special needs, you will be rewarded with a FANTASTIC friend.  His foster family has fostered over 60 dogs and they say he is definitely one of the best foster dogs they have ever had.  Slim is such a polite pup, has wonderful manners, crate trained, potty trained, and gets along great with other dogs and his foster home. He has an awesome personality and demands (and deserves) to be given a lot of attention.   He is a favorite of the vets and techs at Friendship vet.  In public, he is outgoing, charming and active.  

His preferred place is sitting on your lap or burrowing under the covers.  Being allowed to sleep in the bed with his new family is a must.   His favorite activities are playing with toys,  patrolling the yard, and being with his humans.   PLEASE  don't let his medical needs scare you away from Slim. He will be such a wonderful addition to you life.   His foster mom will be happy to answer any additional questions you may have, feel free to message her at the address above.

If you want to help with this dog’s medical expenses: 
https://therescuedrescuers.org/how-to-help

If you want to adopt this dog, apply at the link! 
https://therescuedrescuers.org/adoption-application

animal.description:
Gentlemen, start your engines because Mister Jackson is revving to go! This energetic boy is on the fast track to your heart! He's a 45-pound, 1 1/2 -year-old bundle of joy, who's up for a run, fetch, or tug-of-war at any time. If you're looking for an outdoor playmate to keep up with your fast pace, then you've found the right guy!

Mister Jackson is dog-friendly, housetrained, and crate trained. With all of his energy, though, he still likes to slow down a couple of times a day for a pit stop to chill in his crate and recharge. Then, he's off to the races again! He is still working on indoor manners that he never learned as a puppy. But with a bit of patience and consistent training, he'll master all of the commands in no time. He's really smart, and he's already made a lot of progress with his training.

Being young, he's curious and wants to grab what he thinks is his and play, play, play! Even though Mister Jackson likes children, he can get a little excited and mouthy, so a home with no children is best for this roadster. A fenced yard is also a must-have; he'll be able to expend some of that energy so it stays outside. And cats? Probably not
as
Mister Jackson loves to play a little too much for kitties.

Mister Jackson is a very happy, friendly dog with great outside manners. He's a super pal to take hiking or to a social event. He loves walks and is ready to go in an instant! After all of his energy slows down, he'll sleep like an angel in his crate all night long - while recharging to hit the track again the next day! He needs a leader to keep up with him and dedicate the time to continue working on his training! Mister Jackson is going full throttle to the finish line. He's ready to meet you in the Winner's Circle today!

For inquiries, email inquiry@angelsrescue.org

An Adoption Application for this dog can be found and submitted online at http://www.angelsrescue.org/adopt/adoption-formsPlease be sure to like our Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/angelsrescue.

*Some of our animals receive a high volume of applications, and we strive to select the best home for each animal. However, we have many wonderful homeless pets available.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.This big fella was originally a stray in a Missouri pound - and when his family didn't come for him, that reached out to a few rescues in Iowa to take him in and find a new forever family. He was given the name Sirius before making it to Safe Haven....but we quickly figured out his name was likely given to him because of his striking blue eyes. 'Sirius' is a greek name meaning 'glowing' and is also the name of the brightest star in the sky. 'Sirius' is also a popular character in Harry Potter that could turn into a dog - so we agree this name is perfect for our pretty unique new dog. His breed is a guess, but those big blue eyes and thick coat certainly make us think he is part Husky. Sirius is a big, solid fella that seems to love everyone he meets. We aren't quite sure if he gets along with other dogs yet, he does seem a bit reactive, but may be okay if properly introduced. We do know Sirius would love a fenced in yard or someone to jog with, as he is a very active fella and is happiest when he gets lots of exercise. He is a smart dog, knows a few basic commands and seems very willing to learn. He really wants to find 'his person' to bond strongly with and will provide a lifetime of love and devotion! ** UPDATE 1/16/21 - Sirius was adopted 5 months ago from Safe Haven. His family reports that he is a great dog that loves long walks and snuggling on the couch! What he doesn't like is being woken up.....he will growl if you wake him up. Unfortunately this behavior escalated in his adoptive home, and when one of the kids hugged a sleeping Sirius, he did react - he was startled and did bite the kid :( So Sirius was returned to Safe Haven and is looking for a dog savvy home that can respect the space that Sirius needs when sleeping. Interested in adopting this pet? Please click the adoption info link for more information. And then click on the 'Online Application' link at the bottom of that page.

Adoption Info

animal.description: Benny says hello! He is on the look out for his new forever home! Benny loves to play in water, especially the hose outside. Benny is still a puppy so he loves to play, his foster mom says he is very spunky and he loves to talk! Benny will have to be walked on a leash as he loves to chase cars he’s thinks he can drive. He did have an injury on his lower leg when he first came to us but it has now healed, zzz Benny will thrive as an o my dog in home as he can be selective at times with dogs.  He is not very fond of crates and he will try and break down the sides to get out but we are working on correcting that issue he loves to roam the house and be around his people.  Benny loves to try and chase anything that is moving fast, squirrels, cars, lizards so he will be a great running buddy.  He is a sucker for belly rubs! Benny does not realize his size and will jump up when excited or play a little rougher but he is not aggressive and we’re working on no jump.  He is just a big teddy bear. Benny is ready to find his forever home!

Hey friends, I'm Shylow! I'm super excited to meet you! I love everyone I meet-dogs and humans. Really, everything about life is fun & exciting for me. I'm your typical young labrador mix - happy, sweet, goofy, playful, and energetic! I'm about 1-1/2 years old and weigh about 65 pounds.

I really enjoy playing with other dogs whose size and energy are a good match for me. My tiny foster fur brother snaps at me because I'm a bit too enthusiastic, so I would like a home where I can play with another dog my own size! Probably big kids would be best for me because I'm pretty sure I will knock young children over by accident. I'm working on that as well as all of my manners and I am a quick learner. I love my crate, sit nicely for treats and I understand now that it is not good to chew TV remotes. I will just stick to the toys in my basket! I would love a family who will spend time with me, help me get the exercise I need and continue helping me with my training. My dream home would have another dog and a fence.

If you are looking to add some fun and laughter to your life, I'm your boy!

If you are looking to add some fun and laughter to your life, I'm your boy!

For inquiries, email inquiry@angelsrescue.org

animal.description:
Hello. My name is Rocky, aka Rockstar aka YBT (yellow belly traitor)… read on and you'll understand. 

I am a middle aged (4.5 year old) hunk looking for a forever home. I am not described as tall, dark and handsome but I am the strong, silent type. I have excellent manners in the house, and do not chew or destroy anything. I love, love, love food. I will go to my bed and wait eagerly to be told its okay to go to my bowl and eat. My two favorite activities in the world are walks and car rides! I love, love, love to go for walks—so much so that my favorite people in the world are the dog walkers. I’m a terrific and eager car rider. I love to go on adventures. I also love to have my head, ears and butt scratched. My social skills with other dogs still need a bit of work, as does my leash work – to be honest, I pull a bit because I love to go for walks. But not everyone is perfect, right? Oh and I have allergies. I will obey basic commands quite well – sit, stay, come, back up, down, and crawl. I never try to run away, even on the rare occasions when I get the opportunity. I also don’t chase anything.  And I mean nothing — not cats, not squirrels, not tennis balls, not squeaky toys, not deer, not even wild turkeys. Nothing, that is, except food.  My foster mom and foster grandma both throw kibble across the room, and I love to chase it and eat it. Truth be told, I have been known to get into the garbage if you leave it out and it smells like food, and the other day I ate a chicken sandwich that had been left on a plate on a table just my height – but, hey, what red-blooded American dog wouldn’t?  My ideal future home would be with a strong, calm individual(s), who can be my leader. A leader who will take me on many long walks, preferably at a good clip, and who is happy to have me as an only dog, although I might be super happy with a submissive, non-reactive doggie friend. I also need someone who will give me a little time to trust them. Respectful children in the home should be fine, as should cats with a proper and gradual introduction. I presently live with rabbits and, although I haven’t been granted the freedom to interact with them too much, I also haven’t shown any interest in them — even though one of them seems to want to check me out.  If you think we might be a good match, please reach out to my friends at K9 Kismet.  
K9 Kismet Adoption Application-https://k9kismet.org/forms/ 

In a nutshell:

Medical: allergies requiring allergy drops before meals and periodic veterinary. 

Behavior: Very quiet dog.  Calm at home, and not destructive, even when left alone.  Does well with confident people, especially those who take him places and convey that they like him.  Is a good watch dog and will warn perceived intruders.  May need time to develop trust. Is not socialized with dogs; seems to want to meet other dogs but can stare at dogs out on walks and will react if seemingly attacked. May growl if disturbed at night while resting in his bed; needs to be woken/roused verbally not through touch. When in an excited state, may forget obedience and listening skills. Pulls on leash and zigzags. He is crate trained. Has basic+ obedience, and is very food motivated, making him easy to train. He is not food possessive with people.

Likes: being scratched, car rides, walks, food, and adventures, including going on vacation and staying in hotels

animal.description:
I'm Really Nice Boy!
Max was born about August 30, 2010 and weighs too much at about 60 lbs. He is definitely Beagley, but seems to be a bit larger and longer than normal so there could be some Basset mixed in. Whatever breed he may be he is about the sweetest guy you'd ever want to meet. He is also quiet, which we really appreciate. He is wonderful with the other dogs, loves to go for rides, is house trained and fine with children. He is with us because his human father had to take a job where he would be away for 10-12 hours a day and this was back in 2014.

Max was adopted a few times and always returned. The first time is was because he couldn't be alone and it was much less alone than he was used to. Then the next two times we found humans home much or all the time and then their lives changed. When Max came back the third time and realizing what was happening and it was obvious his heart was hurting our amazing team of volunteers asked us to not put him back up for adoption and let him be a sanctuary pet at Joyful Rescues. Which he has been and he is very, very, happy here with all the dogs and there is at least one human here at ALL times. A volunteer once thought she'd try to foster him and found that she could not even take a shower without him becoming destructive trying to get to her. So, Max came back the same day. We LOVE this guy and he LOVES the volunteers and staff at the main location - Max is living his best life - the best life for him.

animal.description:
Tracer came from a hoarding situation where, as a puppy, she was kept in a large, dirty pen with many other dogs. She was not socialized with people, so she is generally a shy dog. She is very sweet once she settles in, and she LOVES going for runs! Any home for Tracer would need to walk or run with her and preferably have another playful dog.

Tracer would be most comfortable in a harmonious household with someone who stays home, more than they are away. She also loves other dogs and would really like a doggie friend to play with. Anyone getting to know her, really needs to give her about 3 weeks to settle in. Once she does, we promise she will not disappoint! She would prefer a home without small children. 

If you are reading this, we are still accepting applications on this pet. 

Our Adoption Process:


	Meet the Adoption Criteria. Before you do anything else, make sure you meet our adoption criteria. You must be at least 21 years old. You must live within a 60-mile radius of Richardson, Texas. You must share veterinary records for all pets currently in your home and all pets owned in the last five years. All pets in the home must be spayed or neutered. If you rent your home, you must provide verification that pets are allowed on the property. You must be willing to be interviewed by an adoption counselor and you must undergo an in person or virtual home visit from an RHS representative.
	Complete Application. https://www.richardsonhumanesociety.org/adopt/
	Phone Interview. Compatible applicants will be forwarded to a counselor who will contact the applicant for a phone interview.
	Home Visit. If all the steps above are completed satisfactorily, we will set up a visit where you can meet the pet you are interested in. We will try to include the foster parent so you can learn more about how the pet is in a home environment.
	Complete Adoption. If all feel it is a good match, we will schedule the adoption at your home or an off-site location. The applicant will need to complete the adoption contract and pay the adoption fee. Our adoption fee is $250 for adult dogs, $300 for puppies (under 1 year) and $125 for cats. Discounts are available for senior-aged pets.

animal.description:
Poor Brandie (see my other photos & watch my video new video!) was neglected matted thin had no vet care and lived in a backyard. She was shy and nervous at the shelter and hid in the corner of her cage. With time staff were able to take her out and carry/pet her. She was ok and ignored other dogs but too distracted to interact. She has had no training and is under-socialized. She needs time to get healthy with holistic/fresh foods learn home training and get groomed. More info. to come while she gets TLC at her foster home. NOTE: She needs a very experience adult home with yard. No other dogs. Growls at other dogs. No kids. She has fear issues.
8/24/20 update: Brandie is very scared at her foster home and will growl when approached by them or their small dog. She needs time to decompress get healthy learn 'home living' and to trust people. She will not walk on leash. Needs grooming and then her spay surgery. Brandie will need weeks to month of rehab so she will not be available for a few weeks to month. No apartments for her. She needs experienced adult home with attached backyard for potty biz. No apt. In a few weeks when she feels safe and we learn more about her personality we will contact matching applicants. She needs a very experienced guardian and adult home only.
9/7/20: Video of her finally feeling safe and happy. Still using pee pads and learning house-training. She is still scared to be leashed and won't go out for walks yet. She is great with husband. Still afraid of collar and won't walk on leash. Need to work on house-training to go to yard. Need very patient and experienced guardian. She growls at the foster home's dog still. So home with no other dog.
10/11/20: Now with single lady foster home. She warmed up with foster mom. Active inside home. Need home with yard to continue to try to get her out. Still using pee pads in the house and afraid to be leashed for walks. She is still fearful of other dogs and will growl at them. Will need more time. Need very experience adult-only home.
10/29/20: She is now totally relaxed at home but she is not the cuddle type she ran away when trying to hug her. She is comfortable going out to the yard by herself now. We just started to have short walk outside the house about 10 minutes she was very scared at first shaking and pooping. But after a while she is ok. She is not good with toys. She chewed off pieces tried to swallow. She likes to play with the tennis ball. Also she runs away each time I have something on hand except food. She has a collar now it still takes a while to hook on the leash. Seems not possible to wipe her or comb her. She can go to bathroom indoor and outdoor. But for outdoor there must be no access to the wee pad then she will go outside. If she has a choice she will use the pad. I left the patio door open so she can go anytime. There are home visits with other dogs she was very scare and hide away. She is definitely a work in progress still but has come a long way.
12/22/20: Brandie is now going out to walk no problem. We go out two times a day. She is not a cuddle type as of now she stays on my lap for about 8-10 minutes and wants to go back to the floor. Not ready for belly rub. I tried to clean her paws after walks she is not happy and growls and tried to nip. Her bed is her territory once she is in she will growl and even tried to nip if you disturb her (petting or putting blanket on her) She is a sweet girl but you must know her character a strong leader will be good for her. When we walk outside and meet other dogs she shakes a lot and hides behind me when the other dogs come to her even other people just talk to me she is shaking and hiding behind me. We went hiking she has no problem as long as we don't see any other dogs.YouTube: https://youtu.be/PzRnRFfNcvY

animal.description:
Carolina Boxer Rescue is a volunteer run, 501(c)3 non-profit organization. Our mission: To balance the health, safety, and welfare needs of Boxers in the Carolinas (and parts of Virginia and Georgia) by providing a loving and safe environment for stray, abused, impounded and owner surrendered dogs by placing them in foster homes and ultimately - forever homes.

________________________________________________________________________________________

Dog's Name: Josie

Dog's Approximate Age: 3 years

Gender: Female

Dog's Size: Medium (50lbs to 70lbs. as adult and healthy weight)

Dog's Weight: 54 pounds

Good with small dogs?: Don't know yet

Good with big dogs?: Yes

Good with cats?: Yes

Good with kids?: Yes, all ages

Any medical issues?: Heartworms

Crate trained?: Yes

House trained?: Yes

Heartworms?: Yes

9/20/20: Josie is a super sweet girl who is still coming out of her shell. She has warmed up to women faster then men, but is finally trusting of my husband now. She has been around dogs of all sizes and breeds, as well as kittens, and has done fantastic with them. She is not food aggressive at all, and knows her own bowl. She is crate trained and house trained, and uses our dog door like a champ. She is currently not fond of walking on a leash outside of the backyard, but we are working on that and she is getting better with time and patience. She loves to snuggle on the couch with you, and has just started to show her playful side with my senior male boxer. We are still trying to put weight on her since she is not super food motivated. Josie loves her dog toys, and loves on them instead of destroying them. She will be ready for adoption after her heartworm treatment is complete in a few months, and would do best in a home with another dog.

8/24/20: Welcome Josie to CBR. More to come as she gets settled into her foster home!

_____________________________________________________________________________

Come visit carolinaboxerrescue.org to learn more about me and see more pictures. Learn about our adoption process too!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Hi there! My name is

Tiger

and I am almost two years old. I get along with other dogs and I am pretty well housebroken. I am good when left alone, but prefer to be near my person as much as possible. I will play with some squeaky toys, but I prefer attention and cuddling, one could call me a lap dog. Don't get me wrong though, for, as much as I love to cuddle I still do have a lot of energy that I need to get out of me so I have higher than average exercise needs

! I do enjoy being outside and do pretty well on leash though I might prefer a harness over a collar. I have been on some car rides and enjoy them. I might be excited at first, but if you ask me to stay in the backseat I will. Overall I would be a good addition to the right person or family, but I do need someone that can work with me on basic manners (I jump up when I get excited) and continue learning good behaviors so an experienced dog owner who is very familiar with my breed
is a must. I am not a fit with
children or cats.
I will also definitely need a 6 foot fence as I am a bit of an escape artist!

Tigers adoption fee is $250 and includes his neuter, microchip, current vaccinations and preventatives PLUS a free obedience course at Cedar Run in Hiawatha. Last Hope requires that all animals be kept as indoor pets only, be current on preventatives and vaccinations and be altered. Our adoption process includes reference and background checks, a vet check and a home visit. Please submit an adoption application for consideration at www.adopthope.org.

animal.description:
MEDICAL HOLD - NOT AVAILABLE 
Merlin is a 1 year old male Cocker Spaniel and Poodle Mix (our best guess) rescued from a shelter and heartworm positive. He will need to go through expensive and painful treatment that will take a few months. Once treated and cleared by our vet, he will be available for adoption. This probably won’t be until after the first of the year 2021. If you would like to donate toward his care, please visit our website www.luv4k9s.org and select the Donate button for our PayPal account. 

He will not be available for adoption until treatment is complete. At that time, if you think you would be interested in adopting him please complete our no obligation application and we can start the process at www.luv4k9s.org. Select Available Dogs then scroll down to application, complete and submit. 

A physical secure fence attached to the residence is a requirement to adopt a dog from our rescue. Invisible fence doesn't meet this requirement. No exceptions.

Our adoption area is primarily OHIO. We will consider KENTUCKY, AND INDIANA AND CERTAIN AREAS OF MICHIGAN, WEST VIRGINIA, AND PENNSYLVANIA if it’s the best fit for the dog.

WE DO NOT SHIP NOR ARRANGE TRANSPORTS.

THE APPLICATION MUST BE COMPLETED AND SUBMITTED BEFORE WE CAN START THE PROCESS. 

IT CAN TAKE AT LEAST 2 WEEKS TO PROCESS AN APPLICATION SOMETIMES LONGER DEPENDING ON VOLUNTEER AVAILABILITY AND NUMBER OF APPLICATIONS RECEIVED SO PLEASE BE PATIENT. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters must understand that each home is different, and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. 
Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for:
1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (ex. a 4 month old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break) 
2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old, to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise.
3.) Socialization: The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home.
4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded tenfold, for years to come.
Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy. Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time consuming and can be expensive. All Dogs Require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well-trained, well socialized dog is more than worth the effort put in to get them there. 

Our adoption fee includes spay/neuter, routine shots, rabies, worming, microchipped, heartworm testing and they are on monthly preventative. Visit our website www.luv4k9s.org for more information and to complete an application.

animal.description:
Isadora (also know as Schnozette and Izzy) is approximately 8-10 years old, she is a Miniature Bull terrier weighting around 45lbs. She has had a tough life (she looks a disaster- stained, scarred and calloused), but is the happiest, sweetest, most care free girl you could ever meet! She has a great spirit and she is always smiling and tail wagging! Izzy loves her dog pal friends (her size and larger, has not been around small dogs while in our care) and considerate people of all ages, even though she is like a little bull in a china shop,haha. However, NO KITTIES please, she is not a fan! Izzy does not like the crate, but has acclimated pretty well with treat motivation. She cannot go long periods of time without going outside to pee. It does not seem to be a medical issue, we think she was most likely always a outdoor dog and not custom to indoor life. She is a strong little gal, walks fairly well on leash most times though. Izzy is pretty active for her age, but also enjoys lounging at your feet and on her bed.

Isadora does suffer from chronic ear issues that require daily medication to keep her comfortable, the years and years of neglect make it impossible to remedy the situation, just manage it. Other than that she will not take much to keep happy and comfortable and we guarantee this gal is well worth it! In addition to being spayed, heart worm tested and up to date on vaccines, we recently had a full dental cleaning done!

animal.description:
Darla came to us from a shelter in the panhandle of Florida. They thought she was pregnant, but turns out she was just chubby and had heartworms. Darla has been treated and is healthy and ready for a new home now. Darla absolutely loves people - ALL of them, kids included. However, she does not care for other animals and would do best as the only pet in the home. Darla LOVES toys and used to carry around a squeaky rubber cow until he fell apart. She is very smart and willing to please her person. She is active and would do best in a home where she gets lots of play time.

Please visit our website at faithfulfriendsrescue.org/adoptable-pets if you are interested in adopting.

I am a mixed breed dog. This means I don't have a specific recognizable breed. The rescue uses the following guide which are guesses based on my current size and age for how big I will be when full grown: Mixed Breed (small) up to 25 pounds - Mixed Breed (medium) between 25-45 pounds - Mixed Breed (large) more than 50 pounds. For more information on, please visit the website https://faithfulfriendsrescue.org/adoptable-pets.

animal.description:
Blue is one of the most beautiful Chows we ever did see. We don't know much about her past, but we can tell by her demeanor that she likely has a pretty horrible story to tell. If only dogs could speak to us. We pulled Blue from South Carolina at the beginning of the year. We were told she was food aggressive, but that didn't scare us because we have worked with that many times before. We don't know if the traveling north changed her (sometimes the trip can traumatize a dog) or if the previous shelter was not completely truthful about her behaviors. The first few days we had her we could not safely touch her. She never bit us, but we also didn't give her the chance to. We could tell by her body language that she wanted nothing to do with us. We decided to give her a few days to decompress because sometimes that is all a dog needs. She did get better after a few days. She began letting us slip lead her and we were learning to understand her body language better. Her play often appeared aggressive to us, so we had to learn how to tell the difference. She was a bad cage fighter and would freak out in her kennel if she had food and someone walked by. One time she did bite one of our employees when we were putting her food down for her. Thankfully it was more of a warning bite and she didn't break skin. She immediately released and backed up because she knew she had done something wrong. It was at this point that we realized her only hope was a professional trainer. Thankfully she got extremely comfortable with our director. Our director could handle her without a problem, feed her, bathe her, and really do anything to her. This showed us that there is hope for this sweet girl. She just needed to learn that life isn't as scary as she thinks.

We got Blue enrolled with an amazing trainer. He evaluated her and determined that there is hope for her. As soon as he gave us the okay, we enrolled her in his board and train program. She has been there for a little over a month and will be spending about another month there. She has made huge improvements. She is playing with other dogs, she doesn't give them a hard time about going in and out of her kennel and she is learning to not be protective over her food. She is a completely different dog than the once scared and aggressive girl we knew. 

Blue will need a special type of owner. One that is going to stick with her training and not let her become the boss. She needs to know who is in charge so that she doesn't go back to the way she was. We don't think it would be safe for Blue to share a home with a child at this time, but we will update if that changes. We think she could happily live with another dog, but we don't know how she is with cats. She would love a huge yard to play in and people to play games with. Whoever adopts Blue will get multiple training sessions with her trainer before taking her home, that way they know everything she needs. The sessions will be paid for by us. 

Blue's adoption fee is $500. She will require 5 visits to our facility with our trainer before going home. Once she is home, we will have our trainer visit 3-5 times to help her adjust. We will cover the cost of these 10 training sessions.
