animal.description:
Meet the beautiful dog who made us work for her trust, Mama Meadow. This beauty is around 5 years old, 45lbs, and a mom to 11 adorable puppies. This wonderful girl has one sad story to tell. Meadow was a stray who found herself on some pretty awesome peps property around July 27th. They tried to catch her but she was not having anything to with this. They begun feeding her to earn her trust. Meadow did not make this process easy at all. However, with presistence and patience their hard work paid off. On 8/18 during the thunder storm we had the couple trying to help Meadow was able to capture her in their horse trailer. At this point Meadow was VERY pregnant and we wanted to help her and her soon to be kiddos. Meadow was very fearful upon arrival and sadly this made it hard to find a foster home. That didnt stop us from giving Meadow the best set up here on site! Shortly after arrival,
 labor day to be exact, Mama Meadow blessed us with 11 adorable puppies. All of Meadows puppies have found their forever homes now its Meadow turn. We are still learning about Meadow but she continues to come more and more out of her shell daily. Do you have room in your heart for Mama Meadow? Can you show her just all the good life has to give and show her just how wonderful love is? If so please send us an application so we can make it happen! You may apply at mendohumanesociety.com 



TRANSFORMATION IN PROGRESS:
Last night (8/17/20) our phones blew up with tags, messages and calls to help this sweet mama dog. The story was that a nice family had spotted this scared dog on their property 3 weeks ago and have been diligently working to gain her trust. They were not able to get close but a feeding routine kept her hanging around and soon they noticed that she was very pregnant. Yesterday evening with the loud thunder and crazy weather they were able to get her contained in this horse trailer. And this morning our team answered the call for help and got her to safety. This very scared girl was found way up Deerwood Drive in Ukiah, if you know where she belongs please give us a call! For now she is resting comfortably in our maternity suite and we will be working on gaining her trust. Rescue missions like this are made possible because of our team and the support we receive from our community! Getting her to safety was step one but the journey is not over yet. We run entirely on the donations from our community and now we need to get this whole family vetted and healthy. Will you help us by donating to their care? Donate below and please share!

If you are looking to donate supplies we need large crates and good quality puppy kibble and canned food.

Stay tuned for updates on our new friend. Big thank you to her finders for all their work caring for her over the last few weeks. We are so glad we get to help this little family through this difficult time.

Please spay and neuter your pets 


For more info call us at 707 485 0123 or email dogteam@hsimc.org

He is a very happy, friendly guy with the cutest ears you've ever seen! He was a stray that turned up down the street from the shelter. So he decided to walk himself over, turn himself in and find out about these forever homes everyone keeps talking about! Mac is in urgent need of a home with the family he deserves! Mac is good with other friendly dogs and can be tested with cats upon request. 

Adoption fee: $150; includes spay or neuter, vaccinations (dhlpp and rabies), deworming for intestinal parasites and flea treatment. Heartworm test (including first 30 days of prevention) can be added for an additional $20.

Rescue inquiries can be sent to Friendsofbcacga@gmail.com or you can call the shelter directly at 478-445-5514 and leave a voicemail for a call back from the Rescue and Adoption Coordinator.

The Baldwin County Animal Shelter is often operating at capacity, this means that for every dog or cat that comes in, another must leave via rescue or adoption, or risk being euthanized for space.  Multiple dogs and cats come to the shelter EVERY DAY, which means animals must also be moving out at the same rate. Unfortunately, sometimes there are larger adult, "pitbull" or mix-breed dogs that are continually overlooked for their younger or more "adoptable" counterparts. Please consider adopting a new best friend today!

animal.description:
***PLEASE DO NOT CONTACT AUSTIN DOG RESCUE REGARDING THIS DOG. PLEASE CONTACT THE PERSON LISTED BELOW IN THE AD FOR MORE INFORMATION***

THIS IS A COURTESY LISTING. ADR is not responsible for the health, temperament, behavior or placement of this dog. Listings are done at the request of the dog's owner and as an outreach and community service in hopes of finding these dogs a loving, stable forever home. Placement decisions are made solely at the discretion of the owner and not Austin Dog Rescue. Owners are required to ask for an adoption fee from adopters.

This is the information that we received from Malo's current family:

This is our boy Malo, and as it breaks my heart to do this - we are having to rehome him. Malo is a year and a half (almost two) Pitbull Terrier puppy who we adopted from the shelter at the beginning of this year. He's neutered, up-to-date on all of his shots and is currently on flea and tick medication. He truly is an amazing dog, but not the right fit for a family with young kids. He has a lot of energy, and is very much still a puppy. He needs a family that can respect his boundaries, but also give him the love, affection, training he needs and the time to run his energy out. We are rehoming him because we have two young kids, and from what we’ve seen, he is not a fan of all the loud noise and chaos and kids intruding in his space. We suggest he is the only pet as he isn’t fond of cats (we’ve never seen him interact with any, but every time he sees them through our window, he immediately starts barking, and wanting to chase them) and we’ve tried introducing him to one dog, and neither dog was having it - by that, I mean it didn’t seem like a good fit ,so we separated before anything physical could go on. Although the paperwork we have from the shelter said he did good with his kennel mate and a few other dogs, so maybe we just went about the introduction wrong. As far as behavior goes, he is very high-strung, and has a ton of energy. He knows basic commands such as "sit," "stay," "shake," "drop it"(he loves chewing on toys) and "kennel up." He is very vocal, and will let you know when he has to go potty by barking until you let him out (he’s also potty trained lol) he does have a tendency to get mouthy, and by that I mean like when a puppy is playing, and they use their teeth. I feel like he was possibly never trained out of that behavior. He has never bit anyone in a forceful or aggressive manner - we have been working on training him out of that.

If you are interested in meeting this gorgeous guy, please contact Katie at: katieajones97@gmail.com

Note: A small re-homing fee will apply to ensure a good home.

animal.description:
**PLEASE NOTE - CHA CHA NEEDS A QUIET, EXPERIENCED HOME WITH ANOTHER DOG AND A FENCED-IN YARD**

Cha Cha is a 1 year old spayed female lab/beagle mix who weighs 31 lbs. Cha Cha was rescued from an overcrowded shelter after being seized from a horrible hoarding situation with a few friends who have since found their forever homes. The conditions she was forced to live in were absolutely deplorable, and she can be quite nervous in new situations as a result. It's clear that she hasn't had many positive interactions with humans before she was saved, so she is looking for a patient, loving family that will teach her that the world and the people in it aren't so scary after all. She needs a quiet home without children and a family with dog experience. Cha Cha absolutely loves being around other dogs and seems to gain confidence from her canine pals, so we are requiring that her forever home have another dog or two that can help show her the ropes. She is still learning how to walk on a leash, so her forever home must have a securely fenced-in yard that she can practice her leash walking skills in. We have already seen such an amazing transformation in Cha Cha in her foster home and can't wait to watch her continue to transform. When she sees her foster mom, her whole body wiggles in excitement! Cha Cha endured unimaginable neglect in her past, but we have promised her only good things from here on out. Watching a shy dog transform with love, patience, and time is an incredibly rewarding experience, and we cannot wait to watch Cha Cha blossom as she continues to learn how great a dog's life can be. Please help us find Cha Cha the loving, patient forever family she so desperately deserves! 

Interested in adopting? Take the first step and complete an adoption application on our website: https://www.all4pawsrescue.com/
We are a foster based organization so we do not have a facility to visit. Please visit our FAQs to learn more: https://www.all4pawsrescue.com/faq
Find us on Facebook for foster updates and a full list of our adoptable pets: https://www.facebook.com/all4pawsrescue/

- Enjoys following you all around the house and just wants to be with you
- Likes to snuggle on your lap or lay right up next to you! As long as part of him is touching you he is content!

- Does well in the crate but has also proven himself to be worthy of being left out of the crate while foster mom is not home
- Walks well on leash
- Not looking to go to dog parks/dog bars
- Has not been tested with cats


Before emailing- please read:
- Yes, this dog is available for adoption
- The adoption fee for Axel is $256
- Apply at c2cnd.org

animal.description:
Piper is very easy on introduction. She isn't in your face about meeting you, but she is just so sweet once you decide to approach her. If you reach out to make friends, she will decide to be your BFF immediately. 
I think she would benefit with more leash walking, but she was NO trouble. She is also quite small so it is very easy to manage any tugging. Honestly, I was prepared for a much longer walk, but she wore out and flopped down panting after a block!. I took her back to my house and decided to just chill with her for a few hours outside. I found out this little lady is just a love bug. She wants to stare into your eyes in bliss as you give her belly rubs. This girl was gentle, loving, and showed me signs of extreme intelligence. I think she would be easy to train if we could figure out what she would ""work"" for. (She doesn't respond to balls as prizes!) 
She saw many neighborhood dogs on our walk, and was super happy (play stance!) when she saw small dogs. All of the larger dogs in the 'hood were having some fence aggression, and her reaction to these was to have hackles. I'm not sure how she would respond to a larger friendly dog, but I do think testing her with friendly smaller dogs would be the way to start. I wouldn't doubt that she is 100% friendly with all other FRIENDLY dogs. Honestly, I think she would do well placed in a home with anyone that doesn't have small small kids. Even a nonactive home would probably be fine for her. She might need some puzzles and chew toys to keep her brain stimulated, but she wasn't super energetic! She really just wants to snuggle!

animal.description: Hi! My name is Diva and I am a 6 month old border collie x heeler mix.  I got my name because, like Mariah, Whitney and Celione, I like to be the center of attention and the queen of the castle.  Me and my siblings were found in a field in a rural part of Utah when we were just 6 weeks old and taken to the  animal shelter.  It was pretty scary in the shelter; but then we were rescued by Herding Haven and now we live in a wonderful foster home. My foster mom and dad are nice; but, people still make me a little nervous.  I am very shy when I first meet new people, but, with patience (and yummy treats) I gradually warm up.   I LOVE other dogs, especially big, playful ones.  I would really like a home with another dog to help me with my social skills and would prefer not to live with little/young kids (they scare me).   Big kids are ok.  I am super smart and did I mention my ears are HUGE?!?! I am crate-trained, almost fully potty trained and up-to-date on my vaccinations.  If your are interested in completing and application for me, please contact kathie@herdinghaven.org

animal.description: When puppy Gus was 6 weeks old some evil person threw 2 different chemicals on his face.  When he came into rescue it was not know if he would make it or not. But with lots of extra care and love he pulled through.   His mouth and eyes were closed shut due to the chemicals and he had so many blisters in his mouth that we had to purée food for him and syringe feed him for 6 weeks.  Because of the chemicals he is partially blind. He doesn’t see too well in the dark and hesitates walking in a strange place or if furniture is moved around in a different place. He loves anyone he meets, never meets a stranger.  He likes toys and treats. And massages.  Boy does he love massages.  And belly rubs.  He is very strong and is about 75 To 80lbs. So he would be best with kids over 10-12 yrs because of his size   His tail is very strong when he wags it  He will sit or lay down when asked. He kennels very well. Puppy Gus does not like to go outside by himself he wants someone to be with him when he goes out.  He is not a big barker Either. He would love to be someone’s baby with lots of love and attention.  Such a sweetheart.  You can see all the scars still on his face and under his chin and neck. His eyes have a purplish color in them because of the evilness done to him. His adopt fee is 95.00. Call Trish at 901-482-9921 for more info on sweet puppy Gus.  He is in the Provo/salt lake city area as our rescue organization has moved here to utah.

I’m a lab/pitbull mix puppy born in early July 2020. I was rescued from an over crowded shelter along with my two sisters. My sisters have long been adopted, but I’m still patiently waiting for my furever home. 
Look, I’m a total sweetheart! I love other dogs, kids and cats. Everyone! And I think you’ll love me!!
I’m about 30 lbs currently and expected to be in the medium to large size range when fully grown. I would make the perfect addition to any family!

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our dogs are healthy, spayed/neutered, vaccinated and on heartworm preventative. They live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. Many have basic obedience skills and all have been temperament tested. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

Poppop has diabetes and because of that, he’s going to need someone who can afford the insulin he needs, as well as grain-free dog food that helps maintain healthy glucose levels.

Other than diabetes, Poppop is a low-maintenance dog.

Although he probably would do best somewhere with a yard, I can see him doing okay in a smaller living space since he mostly likes to nap while in the house and will let you know when he needs to relieve himself.

Poppop does enjoy the company of other dogs.  However, he likes to take time for himself when needed (to nap). He’s also taken to children well. Poppop cannot be around cats, however, since they trigger his hunting instinct.

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Gus. I'm 4 years old and 26 lbs. I'm a short stocky guy. I’m small but my personality is HUGE.  I’m cute, lovable, and fun. BUT, I know this and sometimes act out to see if I can get away with it. It will be important to be a strong, dog-savvy pack leader with me. I will resource guard my toys and treats, can be leash reactive, and am not a big fan of the word NO. I’m good with kids big and small when in a control environment with a pack leader.  I’m a little more wary around men, so will just need a slow, relaxed introduction. Look at this little face (ok, yeah....and my cute little stocky legs)...,come meet me, I’m worth it! 

I do have a bite history. Part of resource guarding is growling and lunging at individuals. This is what I was doing when I bit a previous owner in November 2020.

Educational articles:
3/3/3 Rule;
https://www.rescuedogs101.com/bringing-new-dog-home-3-3-3-rule/?fbclid=IwAR2iv5m7fqk3FieO7LOsstGeGsYYV_F1rJOd1BPxaImofLpcinpYsUbFRWs

Adoption Donations are $250 for an adult, $350 for puppies (a dog under one year of age), and $125 for a senior dog (based on the age of the dog). Adoption donations are to be made via cash, and credit/debit card. There is a $5 fee to run cards.

Please remember to bring a collar and leash (non-retractable) with you the day of the adoption. Note: Martingale collars and slip leads are strongly recommended.

Due to COVID19, we aren't having as many open, public adoption events.  Current schedule is pre-determined meet and greet appointments are Wednesday evenings and on Saturday from 12-2.  
Our adoption center is located at 3602 Lafayette Blvd, Suite 102, Fredericksburg, VA 22408. It's important that you keep an eye on your emails for any changes or updates during the adoption process.

Visit our website for an application to adopt. 
https://www.olddominionhumanesociety.org/adoption-application

Old Dominion Humane Society is a volunteer based organization. We are run completely by volunteers, who also have full time jobs, so we appreciate your patience.  Currently, the average timeframe for a response to your application is 1 week.

Like us on Facebook "Old Dominion Humane Society"
and be a part of promoting forever homes for dogs in need.
#Adopt #Donate #Foster #Volunteer 

Note: ODHS only adopts to Virginia and surrounding states (including D.C.). A $50 out of state fee applies.

animal.description:
Why Choose Me?

*$150 in sponsorship funds available to rescue group!*

Update 12/28: Wow! I can’t believe King has been at the shelter since July and this is only our second update for him! I just keep thinking that someone will pick him, but it hasn’t happened. Because he can be reactive on the fence line to some dogs, we tested him today face-to-face with Serna, a large female dog. He was great! He wiggled and play bowed nicely–I think he’d make a great companion for a friendly female dog! 

King has been treated for heartworms so he’s ready to find his forever family now!

King was the first dog I took out this morning. He was happy to see me, and I was just as happy to be with him. I loved his enthusiasm! He chased a few tennis balls but decided it was just too hot to bring them back. Sitting in the shade getting pets was probably a better choice for such a warm day. 

King is a sweet, friendly fellow who’ll make you smile! To meet King or learn more about adopting or rescuing him, please contact the shelter at 706-613-3540.

You can read more about this dog and check out additional photos here: https://athenspets.net/Adoptables/53881-king/ OR check out our urgent dogs (http://tinyurl.com/Athenspets-FB-URGENT-Dogs) on Facebook!

This dog is currently at Athens-Clarke County Animal Control, located at 125 Buddy Christian Way, Athens, GA. For the most timely information on hours, location, availability and how to adopt, call the shelter any day from 10am-4pm at 706-613-3540 or go to https://www.athensclarkecounty.com/133/Animal-Control.

animal.description:
Bailey 7yr old Male Dachshund/Chihuahua. Bailey weighs 11lbs.

Bailey is a sweet boy of seven years. Though if you ask him it's seven young, not old.  
He is just searching for the perfect lap to sit next to. He likes slow walks around the parks, back scratches, and treats. All of which he would love to share with his new family.
He is a big dachshund and chihuahua mix hitting the scales at ten pounds. Yet, that's what the long walks are for!
Currently Bailey lives in a home with other dogs, ranging from twelve pounds to sixty. He gets along with all of them well. He would do best in a home without young children.


If the animal is under the age of 3 years old or has health issues, a vet reference is required which means you must own a pet or have owned a pet in your name.

Adoption fee of $275. covers all vetting including spay/neuter surgery, vaccines, microchip heartworm test and treatment if needed and any other medical that may be required while in rescue. 

We only do adoptions on Saturday and not all animals are able to attend so if you would like to see a specific animal please let us know so that we can make arrangements for it to be present at the event. Event locations do vary so please check the homepage to find out where we will be this week. Please do not ask us to reduce adoption fees since all fees help us to cover medical expenses for all of our animals, some of which can be very expensive.  Saving lives is not cheap so thank you for your understanding and helping us save as many as possible.

Please email lowcountryanimalrescue@ymail.com for an application.
